{"title_page": "Tax returns of Donald Trump", "text_new": "{{Donald Trump series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\nThe '''tax returns of Donald Trump''', the 45th and current [[President of the United States]] have been the subject of controversy for the past several years, particularly over their not having been made public despite his political career.\n\nBefore Trump announced his candidacy for president, he repeatedly promised to release his tax returns, making such pledges in 2011, 2014 (\"absolutely\") and 2015.<ref name=\"FactPence\"/><ref name=\"Harwell\"/> During [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|his presidential campaign]], Trump first said he would release his returns after they were \"worked on.\u201d<ref name=fivetimes/> Then Trump claimed<!-- Since no evidence has ever been presented that this is true, using \"claimed\" is justified. --> that, because the returns were being audited, he could not make them public, but would do so. No law actually prevents tax returns from being released due to an audit, as emphasized by the [[Commissioner of Internal Revenue|commissioner of internal revenue]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davison|first1=Laura|last2=Talev|first2=Margaret|title=Trump Falsely Says Law Prevents Him Releasing Tax Returns Under Audit|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-05/trump-refutes-democrats-authority-to-obtain-his-tax-returns|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Orion|last1=Rummler|title=IRS commissioner: No rule against releasing Trump's tax returns while under audit|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-tax-returns-irs-commissioner-audit-20ebb0a7-dc47-4177-bf4c-565aa5cfb734.html|date=10 April 2019|website=[[Axios.com]]|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref> Trump later said that voters were not interested in his returns; that \"there's nothing to learn from them\"; and that his tax rate is \"none of your business\".<ref name=\"Harwell\"/>\n\nSince Trump's election, he has refused requests to release the returns, making him one of the few presidents in recent times to not reveal their tax returns. Trump was the first major party nominee since 1976 not to make his tax returns public. Several states have proposed bills that would require presidential candidates to release their tax returns in order to be listed on the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 ballot]]; such a bill was passed by the [[California Legislature]] and signed by Democratic Governor [[Gavin Newsom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/california/story/2019/07/30/californias-newsom-signs-bill-to-force-trump-tax-returns-1122154|title=California's Newsom signs bill to force Trump tax returns|last=White|first=Jeremy|date=July 30, 2019|work=Politico|access-date=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Ways and Means Committee]] of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] made a formal request to the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS), and later issued a [[subpoena]] to the IRS, for six years of Trump's returns, as part of an effort by the committee to evaluate \"the extent to which the I.R.S. audits and enforces the federal tax laws against a president.\"<ref name=WaysMeansSub>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/10/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-subpoena.html|title=House Ways and Means Chairman Subpoenas Trump Tax Returns|first=Nicholas|last=Fandos|date=May 10, 2019|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]] defied the subpoena.<ref name=UPIfinal>{{cite web|last1=Uria|first1=Daniel|title=Mnuchin: Treasury to make 'final decision' on Trump tax returns May 6|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2019/04/23/Mnuchin-Treasury-to-make-final-decision-on-Trump-tax-returns-May-6/8181556063426/|publisher=[[United Press International]]|access-date=April 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rappeport|first1=Alan|title=Steven Mnuchin Refuses to Release Trump's Tax Returns to Congress|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/06/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-mnuchin.html|website=The New York Times|access-date=7 May 2019|date=6 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/10/us/politics/democrats-trump-tax-returns.html|title=House Ways and Means Chairman Subpoenas Trump Tax Records|first=Nicholas|last=Fandos|date=May 10, 2019|website=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mnuchin-defies-subpoena-for-president-trumps-tax-returns-11558123367|title=Mnuchin Defies Subpoena for President Trump's Tax Returns|first=Richard|last=Rubin|date=May 17, 2019|newspaper=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> Upon the Trump administration's refusal to turn over the documents, the Ways and Means Committee filed a suit to enforce the subpoena.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/02/738030272/house-democrats-sue-for-trumps-tax-returns|title=House Democrats Sue For Trump's Tax Returns|author=Kelsey Snell|date=July 2, 2019|website=NPR|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">Quinta Jurecic, [https://www.lawfareblog.com/house-ways-and-means-committee-sues-trump-tax-returns House Ways and Means Committee Sues for Trump Tax Returns], ''Lawfare'' (July 2, 2019).</ref> That case is pending.<ref name=Thomsen/> A draft IRS legal memo, written in fall 2018 and reported in May 2019, concluded that the IRS must provide the requested tax returns to Congress unless Trump invokes executive privilege, contradicting the administration's justification for defying the earlier subpoena.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/confidential-draft-irs-memo-says-tax-returns-must-be-given-to-congress-unless-president-invokes-executive-privilege/2019/05/21/8ed41834-7b1c-11e9-8bb7-0fc796cf2ec0_story.html|title=Confidential draft IRS memo says tax returns must be given to Congress unless president invokes executive privilege|newspaper=Washington Post|date=May 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeparately, the [[House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight Committee]] issued a subpoena to Trump's accounting firm for tax records and other records, as part of the committee's investigation into (1) whether Trump \"may have engaged in illegal conduct before and during his tenure in office\"; (2) whether Trump \"has undisclosed [[conflicts of interest]] that may impair his ability to make impartial policy decisions\"; (3) whether Trump was complying with the Constitution's [[Foreign Emoluments Clause]] and [[Domestic Emoluments Clause]]; and (4) whether Trump \"has accurately reported his finances to the Office of Government Ethics and other federal entities.\"<ref name=DCCirDecision/> Trump sued to block the subpoena; the [[U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]], and later the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia]], rejected Trump's position and have held that the subpoena must be complied with.<ref name=DCtDDCOversight/><ref name=FahrentholdDCCir/><ref name=Hemel/>\n\nIn late August 2019, the Office of the [[New York County District Attorney]] issued a subpoena to Trump seeking eight years of his personal and corporate tax returns, as part of state prosecutors' investigation into [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal|hush-money payments made during the 2016 presidential election campaign]].<ref name=TurnOver>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/07/nyregion/trump-taxes-lawsuit-vance.html|title=Trump Taxes: President Ordered to Turn Over Returns to Manhattan D.A.|last=Rashbaum|first=Weiser|website=The New York Times|date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> Trump sought to quash the subpoena, contending that a sitting president enjoys \"absolute immunity from criminal process of any kind.\"<ref name=TurnOver/> In October 2019, Judge [[Victor Marrero]] of the [[U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York]] rejected Trump's effort to prevent his tax returns from being turned over to the New York grand jury, and ordered Trump to comply with a subpoena. In a 75-page opinion, the court called Trump's contention an overreach of executive power that is \"repugnant to the nation's governmental structure and constitutional values.\"<ref name=TurnOver/><ref name=SDNYDecision>{{cite court|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/07/politics/sdny-ruling-trump-tax-returns/index.html|litigants=Trump v. Vance|vol=395|reporter=F. Supp. 3d.|page=283|opinion=court=S.D.N.Y.}}</ref> The [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] upheld the lower court's ruling in November 2019, rejecting Trump's claim that presidents are immune from state grand jury subpoenas.<ref name=WeiserLiptak>Benjamin Weiser & Adam Liptak, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/04/nyregion/trump-taxes-vance-appeal.html Trump Taxes: Appeals Court Rules President Must Turn Over 8 Years of Tax Returns], ''New York Times'' (November 4, 2019).</ref><ref name=2dCir>''[https://int.nyt.com/data/documenthelper/6407-trump-vance-appeal/a0279d1a81a92e6abce8/optimized/full.pdf#page=1 Trump v. Vance]'' (2d Cir. Nov. 4, 2019).</ref>\n\nSeparately, a [[New York law|New York state law]] was enacted in July 2019, authorizing New York state tax officials to release state tax returns, including Trump's, for any \"specified and legitimate legislative purpose\" to the House Ways and Means Committee and three other congressional committees.<ref name=\"McKinley2019\">{{cite news|last1=McKinley|first1=Jesse|last2=Fandos|first2=Nicholas|title=Cuomo Signs a Bill to Allow Release of Trump's State Tax Returns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/08/nyregion/trump-ny-taxes-cuomo.html|work=The New York Times|date=8 July 2019}}</ref> Trump sued the State and the House Ways and Means Committee fifteen days later to block release of the tax returns.<ref name=\"TrumpSuitNY\">{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/23/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-new-york.html|title=Trump Sues New York and Congress to Shield His State Tax Returns|first1=Nicholas|last1=Fandos|first2=Jesse|last2=McKinley|date=July 23, 2019|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> In November 2019, Trump's suit was dismissed on jurisdictional grounds.<ref name=\"Polantz\">Katelyn Polantz, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/11/politics/donald-trump-tax-returns/index.html Trump can't sue New York state in DC federal court to stop release of tax returns, judge says], CNN (November 11, 2019).</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe IRS has stated that nothing prevents an individual from releasing their tax returns; an audit cannot stop the tax return release, and several former leaders of IRS have said that audits are a poor reason to justify not releasing tax returns. In any case, Trump has the ability to put on hold a current audit. Before Trump's election, every elected president from [[Richard Nixon]] onward has released their tax returns annually. While president, Nixon himself released his tax returns despite them being under audit. Also, all major presidential nominees from 1976 onward released their tax returns.<ref name=WaPoBus/>\n\n==Tax figures from 1985 through 1994==\nTrump lost $1.17 billion between 1985 and 1994 according to 10 years of Trump's tax information obtained by the ''New York Times'', with the amount more than \"nearly any other individual American taxpayer\" during that period. Although Trump has acknowledged the tax-advantaged nature of the real estate business due to large depreciation write-offs to generate losses and reduce tax liabilities, the ''Times'' reported \"depreciation cannot account for the hundreds of millions of dollars in losses.\"<ref name=\"Red\">{{cite news|last1=Buettner|first1=Russ|last2=Craig|first2=Susanne|title=Decade in the Red: Trump Tax Figures Show Over $1 Billion in Business Losses|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/07/us/politics/donald-trump-taxes.html|access-date=May 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|date=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/07/us/trump-tax-figures.html|title=5 Takeaways From 10 Years of Trump Tax Figures|last1=Buettner|first1=Russ|last2=Craig|first2=Susanne|date=May 7, 2019|website=The New York Times|access-date=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/08/trump-defends-tax-tactics-after-nyt-story-says-he-racked-up-more-than-1-billion-in-losses-it-was-sport.html|title=Trump defends tax tactics after NYT probe says he racked up more than $1 billion in losses: 'It was sport'|last=Calia|first=Mike|date=May 8, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=May 8, 2019}}</ref> Due to losing more than $500 million in combined losses, section 172 of the [[Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993]] gave Trump $915.7 million in tax exemption, which he used to pay off 8 years of taxes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/07/us/trump-tax-figures.html|title=5 Takeaways From 10 Years of Trump Tax Figures|last1=Craig|first1=Susanne|last2=Buettner|first2=Russ|date=May 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/103rd-congress/house-bill/2264/text|title=Text - H.R.2264 - 103rd Congress (1993-1994): Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993|last=Sabo|first=Martin Olav|date=August 10, 1993|publisher=[[Congress.gov]]|access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trumps-early-financial-losses-were-so-steep-that-he-did-not-pay-income-taxes-for-eight-years-according-to-new-report/2019/05/07/cb019e4a-7120-11e9-8be0-ca575670e91c_story.html|title=Trump's early financial losses were so steep that he did not pay income taxes for eight years, according to new report|last=Fahrenthold|first=David A.|date=May 5, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Partially leaked returns of 1995 and 2005==\nParts of Trump's 1995 and 2005 tax returns have been leaked.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-times-trump-declared-a-916-million-loss-in-1995-tax-returns/|title=Trump incurrs $916 million loss on his income tax returns|last=Doe|first=John|date=October 1, 2016|work=CBS News|access-date=October 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002062654/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-times-trump-declared-a-916-million-loss-in-1995-tax-returns/|archive-date=October 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trumps-tax-return-leaked-rachel-maddow-what-accountants-think-alternative-minimum-tax/|title=A Trump tax return revealed -- here's what accountants think of it|website=cbsnews.com|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929010525/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trumps-tax-return-leaked-rachel-maddow-what-accountants-think-alternative-minimum-tax/|archive-date=September 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published some tax documents from 1995. ''The New York Times'' reported that the ''Times'' had been given three pages of certain state tax returns for Trump for the year 1995. The materials indicated that Trump incurred a $916 million [[net operating loss]] which, for Federal income tax purposes, could have prevented Trump from owing any Federal income taxes for up to 18 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-times-trump-declared-a-916-million-loss-in-1995-tax-returns/|title=Trump incurrs $916 million loss on his income tax returns|last=Doe|first=John|date=October 1, 2016|publisher=CBS News|access-date=October 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002062654/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-times-trump-declared-a-916-million-loss-in-1995-tax-returns/|archive-date=October 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Marc Kasowitz]] of [[Kasowitz, Benson, Torres & Friedman]] wrote to the ''Times'' stating, according to one report, that \"the publication of Trump's tax records was illegal because Trump had not authorized their disclosure ... [and] threatening 'prompt initiation of appropriate legal action.'\"<ref>Zaretsky, Staci, [http://abovethelaw.com/2016/10/donald-trump-chooses-biglaw-firm-to-fight-new-york-times-over-publication-of-tax-documents/ \"Donald Trump Chooses Biglaw Firm To Fight New York Times Over Publication Of Tax Documents\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617093028/https://abovethelaw.com/2016/10/donald-trump-chooses-biglaw-firm-to-fight-new-york-times-over-publication-of-tax-documents/|date=June 17, 2018}}, ''[[Above the Law (website)|Above the Law]]'', October 3, 2016. Retrieved January 17, 2017.</ref>\n\nTrump claimed on his tax returns that he lost money, but did not recognize it in the form of canceled debts. Trump might have performed a [[Swap (finance)|stock-for-debt swap]]. This would have allowed Trump to avoid paying [[Income tax in the United States|income taxes]] for at least 18 years. An [[Income tax audit|audit]] of Trump's tax returns for 2002 through 2008 was \"closed administratively by agreement with the [[Internal Revenue Service|I.R.S.]] without assessment or payment, on a net basis, of any deficiency.\" Tax attorneys believe the government may have reduced what Trump was able to claim as a loss without requiring him to pay any additional taxes.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/11/01/a-big-dirty-secret-from-donald-trumps-tax-returns-has-been-exposed/ \"A big, dirty secret from Donald Trump's tax returns has been exposed\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210192856/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/11/01/a-big-dirty-secret-from-donald-trumps-tax-returns-has-been-exposed/|date=February 10, 2019}}. ''The Washington Post''. November 1, 2016. Retrieved November 2, 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/04/us/politics/donald-trump-taxes.html \"How a Simple Tax Rule Let Donald Trump Turn a $916 Million Loss Into a Plus\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209120846/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/04/us/politics/donald-trump-taxes.html|date=December 9, 2018}}. ''The New York Times''. October 4, 2016. Retrieved November 2, 2016.</ref> It is unknown whether the I.R.S. challenged Trump's use of the swaps because he has not released his tax returns. Trump's lawyers advised against Trump using the equity for debt swap, as they believed it to be potentially illegal.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/02/opinion/avoiding-taxes-trump-style.html \"Avoiding Taxes, Trump-Style\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230939/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/02/opinion/avoiding-taxes-trump-style.html|date=December 20, 2018}}. ''The New York Times''. November 2, 2016. Retrieved November 2, 2016.</ref>\n\nOn March 14, 2017, the first two pages of Trump's 2005 federal income tax returns were leaked to [[Rachel Maddow]] and shown on [[MSNBC]]. The document states that Trump had a gross adjusted income of $150&nbsp;million and paid $38&nbsp;million in federal taxes. The White House confirmed the authenticity of these documents and claimed: \"Despite this substantial income figure and tax paid, it is totally illegal to steal and publish tax returns.\"<ref name=\"nyt-taxes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/14/us/politics/donald-trump-taxes.html|title=Trump Wrote Off $100 Million in Business Losses in 2005|last1=Baker|first1=Peter|author1-link=Peter Baker (journalist)|last2=Drucker|first2=Jesse|last3=Craig|first3=Susanne|author3-link=Susanne Craig|last4=Barstow|first4=David|author4-link=David Barstow|date=March 15, 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=March 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"hill-taxes\">{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/324016-wh-releases-trump-tax-info-ahead-of-msnbc-report-made-150m-in-2005|title=WH releases Trump tax info ahead of MSNBC report: He paid $38M in federal taxes in '05|last=Jagoda|first=Naomi|access-date=March 15, 2017|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref>.\n\n==Before his presidency==\n{{further|Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nIn 1999, while Trump was considering whether [[Donald Trump 2000 presidential campaign|to run for president]] under the [[Reform Party of the United States of America|Reform Party]], he said \"probably wouldn't have a problem with\" releasing his tax returns if he ran.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kaczynski|first1=Andrew|title=Trump In 1999: I Probably Wouldn't Have A Problem Releasing My Tax Returns If I Ran|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/andrewkaczynski/during-1999-run-trump-vowed-to-release-his-tax-returns|website=[[Buzzfeed News]]|access-date=August 7, 2019|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, Trump said that when President [[Barack Obama]] produces \"[[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|his birth certificate]] ... I\u2019d love to give my tax returns\". [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories#Long form, 2011|Obama's birth certificate was released a week later]], resulting in Trump saying his tax returns would be released \"at the appropriate time\".<ref name=\"FactPence\">{{cite web|last1=Qiu|first1=Linda|title=Pence's False claim that Trump 'hasn't broken' tax return promise|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/oct/05/mike-pence/pences-false-claim-trump-hasnt-broken-tax-return-p/|publisher=[[Politifact]]|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Trump implored for Republican presidential candidate Mitt Romney's tax returns to be released on April 1, which \"historically is the time that everybody gives them\".<ref name=\"WaPoBus\">{{cite web|last1=Harwell|first1=Drew|title=All the excuses Trump has given for why he won't release his tax returns|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2016/09/15/a-running-tally-of-trumps-many-excuses-for-why-he-wont-release-his-tax-returns/|website=[[Washington Post]]|access-date=August 7, 2019|date=September 15, 2016}}</ref> That year, Trump also said that not seeing a presidential candidate's tax returns would lead people to think there was \"almost, like, something wrong. What's wrong?\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Kelly|first=Nora|title=How Hillary Clinton Is Using Her Taxes as a Political Weapon|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/08/clinton-tax-returns-trump/495755/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=August 7, 2019|date=August 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Trump's former political adviser [[Sam Nunberg]] said in 2013 and 2014 that Trump had considered the possibility of releasing his tax returns as part of a presidential campaign, believing that showing how little he paid in taxes would make him appear to be a savvy businessman.<ref name=Ward>[[Vicky Ward]], [https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/14/politics/trump-originally-wanted-to-release-tax-returns/index.html Trump wanted to release his taxes in 2013 to show how smart he was for paying so little], CNN (October 14, 2019).</ref> Nunberg said by November 2014, he had persuaded Trump to reverse course and withhold his tax returns, as Trump decided that he \"wanted to look rich rather than smart.\"<ref name=Ward/> In May 2014, Trump said in an interview: \"If I decide to run for office, I\u2019ll produce my tax returns, absolutely and I would love to do that.\"<ref name=\"FactPence\"/>\n\nIn February 2015, Trump said that if he ran for the presidency: \"I would release tax returns\".<ref name=\"FactPence\"/> On another occasion that month, he declared: \"I have no objection to certainly showing tax returns\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gass|first1=Nick|title=Carson: Trump will release tax returns before election|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/trump-release-tax-records-222887|website=[[Politico]]|access-date=August 7, 2019|date=June 5, 2016}}</ref> Later in February 2015, Trump warned: \"I will tell you upfront ... I want to pay as little taxes as I can as a private person\".<ref name=\"FactPence\"/> In May 2016, Trump voiced similar sentiments, stating he tries \"very hard to pay as little tax as possible\". However, Trump has in 2015 criticized corporate executives and \"hedge fund guys\" for paying zero or negligible taxes. He also alleged in 2011 and 2012 that half of all Americans do not pay income taxes, stating: \"it's a problem\", while noting \"crippling\" government debt. Trump also in 2012 criticized President Barack Obama for \"only\" paying a tax rate of around 20%.<ref name=WaPoBus/> Trump announced his candidacy for President in June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Santucci|first1=John|last2=Stracqualursi|first2=Veronica|title=Donald Trump Announces 2016 Presidential Campaign: 'We Are Going Make our Country Great Again'|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trump-announces-2016-presidential-campaign-make-country/story?id=31799741|work=[[ABC News]]|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Trump was asked by [[Chuck Todd]] if he would release his tax returns, to which Trump answered: \"we'll be working that over in the next period of time, Chuck. Absolutely. [...] at the appropriate time, you'll be very satisfied.\"<ref name=fivetimes>{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=5 things Donald Trump promised he'd do, but hasn't|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/12/13/5-things-donald-trump-promised-hed-do-but-hasnt/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref> In February 2016, Trump said that he would release his tax returns \"[p]robably over the next few months. They\u2019re being worked on now.\"<ref name=fivetimes/> Later that month, Trump said that he could not release his tax returns because he was under audit.<ref name=\"POLITICOtwelve\">{{cite web|last1=Becker|first1=Bernie|last2=Faler|first2=Brian|title=IRS chief: 'Rare' for taxpayer to be audited several years in a row, as Trump claims|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/02/donald-trump-irs-audit-experts-219889|publisher=[[Politico]]|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref> Trump has elaborated that he has been audited for a consecutive \"twelve years or something like that.\"<ref name=\"POLITICOtwelve\"/> In 2016, Trump's tax attorneys have stated that Trump has been under audit since 2002. However, in 2011, 2014, and 2015, Trump made offers to release his tax returns, presumably while he was still under audit.<ref name=\"FactPence\"/>\n\nThe IRS commissioner at the time, [[John Koskinen]], said that an IRS audit does not prevent the taxpayer from releasing tax returns. Koskinen also said that it \"would be rare for anyone to be audited every year\", and that if a past audit revealed no problems, \"it\u2019s a number of years \u2014 two or three at least\" before the IRS would conduct an audit again.<ref name=POLITICOtwelve/><ref name=\"POLITICOtwelve\"/>\n\nThere is no requirement that presidential candidates release their tax returns but candidates are legally free to do so even when under audit.<ref name=release>{{cite news|author=Alan Rappeport|url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/05/11/donald-trump-breaks-with-recent-history-by-not-releasing-tax-returns/|title=Donald Trump Breaks With Recent History by Not Releasing Tax Returns|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106222213/https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/05/11/donald-trump-breaks-with-recent-history-by-not-releasing-tax-returns/|archive-date=January 6, 2019|work=The New York Times|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Stockman>{{cite news|url=http://lawnewz.com/politics/legal-experts-side-with-trump-it-would-be-totally-stupid-to-release-his-taxes-during-audit/|title=Legal Experts Side With Trump; It Would Be Crazy to Release His Taxes During Audit|last=Stockman|first=Rachel|date=May 13, 2016|work=Law Newz|access-date=July 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716130007/http://lawnewz.com/politics/legal-experts-side-with-trump-it-would-be-totally-stupid-to-release-his-taxes-during-audit/|archive-date=July 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Tax lawyers differ as to whether releasing tax returns is legally advisable for someone like Trump who has stated he is under audit.<ref name=Stockman /><ref>Stewart, Emily. [https://www.thestreet.com/story/13687015/1/would-no-tax-lawyer-advise-trump-release-his-tax-returns-it-s-complicated.html \"Would No Tax Lawyer Advise Trump Release His Tax Returns? It's Complicated\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924183723/https://www.thestreet.com/story/13687015/1/would-no-tax-lawyer-advise-trump-release-his-tax-returns-it-s-complicated.html|date=September 24, 2016}}, [[TheStreet.com]] (August 27, 2016).</ref> According to [[NPR]], tax experts, such as [[New York University Law School]] professor Daniel Shaviro, say that \"Trump's lawyers may advise him not to release the returns for legal strategy purposes.\"<ref>Zarroli, Jim. [https://www.npr.org/2016/02/26/468278769/fact-check-donald-trump-cant-release-his-taxes-while-being-audited \"Fact-Check: Donald Trump Can't Release His Taxes While Being Audited?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302140445/https://www.npr.org/2016/02/26/468278769/fact-check-donald-trump-cant-release-his-taxes-while-being-audited|date=March 2, 2019}}, [[NPR]] (February 26, 2016).</ref> In contrast, economist [[Paul Krugman]] argued that Trump should be more willing to reveal his tax information if he were already under audit, as the reveal might have triggered an audit if there was not one.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/democracy-in-america/2016/06/01/the-saga-over-donald-trumps-tax-returns-rolls-on|title=The saga over Donald Trump's tax returns rolls on|date=June 1, 2016|work=The Economist|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714030549/http://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2016/06/donalds-taxes|archive-date=July 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Trump said that he did not plan to release his tax returns before the November 2016 election;<ref name=\"Rappeport\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/05/11/donald-trump-breaks-with-recent-history-by-not-releasing-tax-returns/|title=Donald Trump Breaks With Recent History by Not Releasing Tax Returns|last=Rappeport|first=Alan|date=May 11, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719083106/http://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/05/11/donald-trump-breaks-with-recent-history-by-not-releasing-tax-returns/|archive-date=July 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> the tax returns were not released.<ref name=MoneyWhen>{{Cite web|url=http://money.com/money/5634725/donald-trump-tax-returns-released-2019-democrats/|title=Will Donald Trump's Tax Returns Be Released? Democrats Just Made Their First Move|website=Money|language=en|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217002556/http://money.com/money/5634725/donald-trump-tax-returns-released-2019-democrats/|archive-date=February 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Trump also said in May 2016 that \"there's nothing to learn from\" his tax returns,<ref name=\"Rappeport\"/> and said on [[ABC News]] that his tax rate is \"none of your business\".<ref name=\"Harwell\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trumps-income-tax-returns-once-became-public-they-showed-he-didnt-pay-a-cent/2016/05/20/ffa2f63c-1b7c-11e6-b6e0-c53b7ef63b45_story.html|title=Trump once revealed his income tax returns. They showed he didn't pay a cent.|last=Harwell|first=Drew|date=May 21, 2016|work=The Washington Post|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706210006/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trumps-income-tax-returns-once-became-public-they-showed-he-didnt-pay-a-cent/2016/05/20/ffa2f63c-1b7c-11e6-b6e0-c53b7ef63b45_story.html|archive-date=July 6, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTrump was criticized for his refusal to release tax information. Former Republican presidential candidate [[Mitt Romney]] said, \"It is disqualifying for a modern-day presidential nominee to refuse to release tax returns to the voters.\" Romney speculated, \"There is only one logical explanation for Mr. Trump's refusal to release his returns: there is a bombshell in them.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/05/11/romney-calls-decision-by-trump-not-to-release-tax-returns-disqualifying.html|title=Romney calls decision by Trump not to release tax returns 'disqualifying'|date=May 11, 2016|work=Fox News|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619110559/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/05/11/romney-calls-decision-by-trump-not-to-release-tax-returns-disqualifying.html|archive-date=June 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[John Fund]] of the ''[[National Review]]'' said that Republican convention delegates should abstain from voting for Trump if he does not release the information, fearing that the returns could contain an electoral \"time bomb\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/435254/donald-trumps-tax-returns-delegates-should-abstain-if-he-wont-release|title=Trump's Refusal to Release Tax Returns Is a Ticking Time Bomb for the GOP|last=Fund|first=John|date=May 11, 2016|work=National Review|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718073935/http://www.nationalreview.com/article/435254/donald-trumps-tax-returns-delegates-should-abstain-if-he-wont-release|archive-date=July 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 United States presidential debates]], rival presidential candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] criticized Trump, saying that only \"a couple of years\" of Trump's tax returns were publicly available, \"and they showed he didn't pay any federal income tax\". Trump directly responded: \"That makes me smart.\" Clinton went on to suggest that Trump might not have \"paid any federal income tax for a lot of years\"; this resulted in Trump saying that the taxes he paid \"would be squandered\" by the government.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mangan|first=Dan|title=Trump brags about not paying taxes: 'That makes me smart'|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/09/26/trump-brags-about-not-paying-taxes-that-makes-me-smart.html|publisher=[[CNBC]]|access-date=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==During his presidency==\n{{further|Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency}}\n\nTrump has continued to withhold his tax returns even into his presidency as of September 2019.<ref name=MoneyWhen/>\n\nIn May 2017, Trump said that he \"might\" release his tax returns only after he had stepped down as President. This was in spite of his previous commitment made during his campaign to release his tax returns once they were not under audit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Release his tax returns after an audit is completed - Trump-O-Meter: Broken|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/promises/trumpometer/promise/1421/release-his-tax-returns-after-audit-completed/|publisher=[[Politifact]]|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Tax March protests===\n{{main|Tax March}}\nIn January 2017, an online petition on the \"We the People\" portion of the White House's website calling for the release of Trump's tax returns was set up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/01/petition-didnt-make-trump-give-tax-returns-made-listen/|title=A Petition Didn't Make Trump Give Up His Tax Returns\u2014But It Made Him Listen|last=Ellis|first=Emma Grey|newspaper=WIRED|language=en-US|date=January 26, 2017|access-date=January 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128213639/https://www.wired.com/2017/01/petition-didnt-make-trump-give-tax-returns-made-listen/|archive-date=January 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The petition gained over 1 million signatures, becoming the most signed petition on the White House's website. However, the White House gave no official response to the petition as of April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lam|first1=Bourree|title=The Fight Over Trump's Tax Returns Isn't Over|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/04/trump-tax-march/523116/|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=April 9, 2019}}</ref> Trump spokesperson [[Kellyanne Conway]] then said that \"The White House response is that he\u2019s not going to release the tax returns\" and that \"people didn't care\" about Trump's tax returns.<ref>{{cite news|last=Revesz|first=Rachel|title=Kellyanne Conway says President Trump will not release his tax returns|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/donald-trump-kellyanne-conway-tax-returns-will-not-release-under-audit-conflicts-of-interest-a7540621.html|access-date=7 October 2019|work=The Independent|date=January 22, 2017}}</ref> In response, [[Jennifer Taub]] and others planned the [[Tax March]] on April 15, 2017 ([[Tax Day]]) to demand that Trump release his tax returns;<ref>Amber Jamieson, [https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/12/tax-march-trump-tax-returns-activism-jennifer-taub Tax March: how a law professor sparked a global event to demand Trump's returns], ''The Guardian'' (April 12, 2017).</ref> tens of thousands of people marched in New York and dozens of cities across the country.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/tax-march-protests-demand-donald-trump-to-release-tax-returns/ \"Tax March\" protests demand release of Trump's tax returns], CBS News/Associated Press (April 15, 2017).</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Francescani|first1=Chris|last2=Ramstack|first2=Tom|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-taxes/thousands-at-rallies-demand-trump-release-tax-returns-idUSKBN17H0FW|title=Thousands at rallies demand Trump release tax returns|work=Reuters|date=April 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Congressional requests and subpoenas for Trump's tax returns===\nAfter winning control of the House in the [[United States House of Representatives election, 2018|2018 elections]], House Democrats signaled their intent to use their new power to demand Trump's tax returns in the new Congress, which convened in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/watch/with-house-majority-dems-intend-to-request-for-trump-s-tax-returns-1363758147582|title=With House majority, Dems intend to request Trump's tax returns|website=MSNBC.com|language=en|access-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218175948/https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/watch/with-house-majority-dems-intend-to-request-for-trump-s-tax-returns-1363758147582|archive-date=February 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/donald-trump-tax-returns-democrats-will-demand-presidents-records-house-1205085|title=Democrats set to demand Donald Trump's tax returns after winning House majority|last=Porter|first=Tom|date=November 7, 2018|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328065104/https://www.newsweek.com/donald-trump-tax-returns-democrats-will-demand-presidents-records-house-1205085|archive-date=March 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/806128/once-power-house-democrats-reportedly-demand-trumps-tax-returns|title=Once in power, House Democrats will reportedly demand Trump's tax returns|date=November 6, 2018|website=theweek.com|access-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207165348/https://theweek.com/speedreads/806128/once-power-house-democrats-reportedly-demand-trumps-tax-returns|archive-date=February 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2019, the chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means]], Congressman [[Richard Neal]], formally requested from the IRS six years of Trump's returns.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/08407f0c1bd04a2cb33842ebe8113d82|title=White House pushes back on request for Trump tax forms|first=Marcy|last=Gordon|date=April 4, 2019|agency=Associated Press|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405004721/https://apnews.com/08407f0c1bd04a2cb33842ebe8113d82|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-maneuvers-to-block-release-of-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/04/047b19e0-56f4-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|title=White House maneuvers to block release of Trump's tax returns|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405054133/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-maneuvers-to-block-release-of-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/04/047b19e0-56f4-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The last time a sitting president's tax information was requested was 45 years ago.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The request was made on April 3 via a letter to IRS Commissioner [[Charles P. Rettig]]. It requested both Trump's business and personal returns for the years 2013 through 2018. The deadline he set was April 10, seven days later.<ref name=\"auto\"/> After the first deadline was not met, Neal again wrote to Rettig on April 13, setting a second deadline of April 23, 2019, and writing that a failure to meet the deadline would be \"interpreted as a denial\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lorenzo|first1=Aaron|title=Neal gives IRS commissioner new deadline for handing over Trump's tax returns|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/04/13/irs-trump-tax-returns-1273712|publisher=[[Politico]]|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nUnder a 1924 [[Taxation in the United States|federal tax law]], \u00a7 6103 of [[title 26 of the United States Code]], Congress may request copies of anyone's tax returns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/democrats-want-use-obscure-law-grab-donald-trump-s-tax-n949286|title=Here's how Democrats plan to get Donald Trump's tax returns|website=NBC News|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190118132721/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/democrats-want-use-obscure-law-grab-donald-trump-s-tax-n949286|archive-date=January 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/olc/opinions/1977/05/31/op-olc-v001-p0085_0.pdf|title=Memorandum Opinion for the Acting Commissioner of the Internal Revenue Service - Congressional Access to Tax Returns\u201426 U.S.C. \u00a7 6103(f)|last=Harmon|first=John M.|date=May 2, 1977|website=United States Department of Justice|access-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/6103|title=26 U.S. Code \u00a7 6103 - Confidentiality and disclosure of returns and return information|website=[[Legal Information Institute]]|language=en|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401140541/https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/6103|archive-date=April 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/05/politics/trump-tax-returns/index.html|title=The 1924 law Democrats may tap to see Trump's tax returns|last=Sahadi|first=Jeanne|website=CNN|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307181133/https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/05/politics/trump-tax-returns/index.html|archive-date=March 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[treasury secretary]] is legally obliged to provide the tax returns, and there is no apparent legal mechanism to deny Congress's request.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> On April 5, 2019, Trump's personal lawyer William Consovoy wrote a letter to the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] (the parent agency of the IRS), claiming that the request for Trump's tax information is \"not consistent with governing law\" and that Congress is trying to violate Trump's [[First Amendment]] rights.<ref name=hufffight>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/trump-lawyers-fight-release-of-the-presidents-tax-returns_n_5ca7b38ce4b0dca0330159f4|title=Trump Lawyers Fight Release Of The President's Tax Returns|first1=Andy|last1=Campbell|first2=Arthur|last2=Delaney|date=April 5, 2019|website=HuffPost}}</ref>\n\n====House committees issue formal subpoenas for tax records==== \nOn April 15, 2019, the chairman of the [[House Committee on Oversight and Reform]], Representative [[Elijah Cummings]], issued a subpoena to the accounting firm Mazars USA, LLP requesting tax records and other \"financial documents concerning the President and his companies covering years both before and during his presidency.\"<ref name=DCCirDecision>''[https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=13567751942084956358 Trump v. Mazars USA]'', No. 19-5142 (D.C. Cir. Oct. 11, 2019).</ref> Cummings identified four areas that the committee aimed to investigate through the subpoena: (1) whether Trump \"may have engaged in illegal conduct before and during his tenure in office\"; (2) whether Trump \"has undisclosed [[conflicts of interest]] that may impair his ability to make impartial policy decisions\"; (3) whether Trump was complying with the Constitution's [[Foreign Emoluments Clause]] and [[Domestic Emoluments Clause]]; and (4) whether Trump \"has accurately reported his finances to the Office of Government Ethics and other federal entities.\"<ref name=DCCirDecision/>\n\nOn May 10, 2019, Neal, the chairman of the [[House Ways and Means Committee]], issued a separate subpoena to both the Treasury Department and Internal Revenue Service to hand over six years of President Trump's personal and business tax returns and grant access by May 17.<ref name=WaysMeansSub/> Neal stated that the committee aimed to obtain the tax records to evaluate \"the extent to which the I.R.S. audits and enforces the federal tax laws against a president.\"<ref name=WaysMeansSub/>\n\n====Trump administration defies subpoenas==== \nThe Trump administration refused to comply with the subpoenas.<ref name=Defies>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/17/politics/steve-mnuchin-tax-returns-repsonse/index.html|title=Mnuchin defies House Democrats' subpoenas for Trump's tax returns|author=Lauren Fox|date=May 17, 2019|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name=MnunchinRefusal>{{cite news|last=Rappeport|first=Alan|title=Steven Mnuchin Refuses to Release Trump's Tax Returns to Congress|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/06/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-mnuchin.html|access-date=May 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> On May 6, 2019, after weeks of delay, Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]] sent a letter to House Ways and Means Committee chair Neal, asserting that the subpoena lacked \"a legitimate legislative purpose\" and that \"the department may not lawfully fulfill the committee's request,\" although the IRS released president [[Richard Nixon]]'s tax returns the same day Congress requested them in 1973.<ref name=MnunchinRefusal/> The Trump's administration's [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]], through a memo written by [[Office of Legal Counsel]] head [[Steven Engel]], issued an opinion supporting Mnuchin's refusal to release Trump's tax returns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/14/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-justice-department.html|title=Justice Dept. Backs Mnuchin's Refusal to Release Trump's Tax Returns|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 14, 2019|access-date=June 17, 2019|first=Alan|last=Rappeport|author-link=Alan Rappeport}}</ref> This triggered a legal battle between the administration and Congress.<ref>Andrew Taylor & Jonathan Lemire, [https://apnews.com/ce215295783e419d8896d50bc7907107 Refusal to hand over Trump\u2019s tax returns sets up legal fight], Associated Press (May 7, 2019).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/mnuchin-rejects-democrats-demand-to-hand-over-trumps-tax-returns-all-but-ensuring-legal-battle/2019/05/06/5483f8ac-7022-11e9-9eb4-0828f5389013_story.html|title=Mnuchin rejects Democrats' demand to hand over Trump's tax returns, all but ensuring legal battle|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/justice-dept-issues-memo-backing-mnuchins-refusal-to-provide-trumps-tax-returns-to-congress/2019/06/14/3c8b3376-8ee7-11e9-b08e-cfd89bd36d4e_story.html|title=Justice Dept. issues memo backing Mnuchin's refusal to give Trump's tax returns to Congress|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/07/25/irs-turned-over-nixons-tax-returns-same-day-that-congressional-panel-asked-them/|title=IRS turned over Nixon's tax returns the same day that a congressional panel asked for them|website=Washington Post}}</ref> Neal criticized the administration's position, saying that its objections \"lack merit\" and that \"judicial precedent commands that none of the concerns raised can legitimately be used to deny the committee\u2019s request.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Jeff|title=House Democrats give IRS hard deadline of April 23 to turn over Trump tax returns, say administration's concerns 'lack merit'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/04/13/house-democrats-give-irs-hard-deadline-april-turn-over-trump-tax-returns-say-administrations-concerns-lack-merit/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2019, [[Mick Mulvaney]], Trump's acting [[White House Chief of Staff|White House chief of staff]], said that Trump's tax returns will \"never\" be released.<ref name=Rupar>{{cite web|last1=Rupar|first1=Aaron|title=Mick Mulvaney rewrites history, claims Trump never promised to release his tax returns|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/4/8/18300213/mick-mulvaney-trump-tax-returns-fox-news-sunday|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Itkowitz|first1=Colby|title=Mulvaney says Democrats will 'never' see Trump's tax returns|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mulvaney-says-democrats-will-never-see-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/07/e939deca-593a-11e9-a00e-050dc7b82693_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref> Trump and Mulvaney have argued that voters have no interest in Trump's tax returns and that the issue was \"litigated\" when Trump was elected to the presidency.<ref name=Rupar/><ref name=FOXdeadline>{{cite web|last=Re|first=Gregg|title=Treasury won't meet House Dems' deadline to provide Trump tax returns, Mnuchin says|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/mnuchin-says-treasury-wont-meet-house-dems-deadline-to-provide-trump-tax-returns.amp|publisher=[[Fox News]]|access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' revealed that it had acquired information about Trump's tax returns showing over one billion dollars in business losses with a decade in the red.<ref name=\"Red\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/07/politics/donald-trump-tax-returns-steve-mnuchin-richard-neal/index.html|title=The secret of why Donald Trump won't release his taxes|first=Chris|last=Cillizza|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, a Trump adviser speaking on condition of anonymity told [[Fox News]] that Trump has repeatedly questioned his aides about the status of the congressional request, and also asked about the \"loyalty\" of top IRS officials.<ref name=FOXdeadline/> Trump appointee [[Michael J. Desmond]], who as Chief Counsel of the IRS and Assistant General Counsel in the [[United States Department of the Treasury|Department of the Treasury]] is responsible for giving legal advice to the IRS commissioner, previously served as a tax advisor to the Trump Organization and also worked alongside two other longtime tax advisors to the Trump Organization. According to the ''[[New York Times]]'', on February 5, 2019, Trump asked [[Senate Majority Leader]] Mitch McConnell to speed up Desmond's confirmation and indicating that confirming Desmond was a higher priority to him than confirming [[William Barr]] for Attorney General.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Haberman|first1=Maggie|last2=Fandos|first2=Nicholas|title=Trump Asked That Confirmation of I.R.S. Counsel Be a Priority|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/04/us/politics/trump-michael-desmond-irs.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nTrump and his [[White House Press Secretary]] [[Sarah Sanders]], said that Trump would not release his tax returns while they are under audit,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-maneuvers-to-block-release-of-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/04/047b19e0-56f4-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|title=White House maneuvers to block release of Trump's tax returns|website=Washington Post|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405054133/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-maneuvers-to-block-release-of-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/04/047b19e0-56f4-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> although nothing precludes a person from releasing tax returns that are under audit,<ref name=\"auto1\"/> a fact reaffirmed by IRS Commissioner Rettig.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bruggeman|first=Lucien|title=Treasury to miss Democrats' deadline for Trump's tax returns, he doubles down: 'I won't do it'|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/democrats-deadline-trumps-tax-returns-looms-doubles/story?id=62298329|publisher=[[ABC News]]|access-date=April 28, 2019}}</ref> Sanders also opined that Congress is not \"smart enough\" to examine Trump's tax returns,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Danner|first1=Chas|title=Sarah Sanders: Democrats Aren't 'Smart Enough' to Understand Trump's Tax Returns|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/04/sarah-sanders-democrats-wont-understand-trumps-taxes.html|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> although ten members of Congress are accountants, including three [[Certified Public Accountant]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levenson|first=Eric|title=Sarah Sanders says Congress wouldn't understand Trump's taxes. But 10 members are accountants|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/14/politics/trump-taxes-accountants-congress/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, Trump made a partially false statement that \"There\u2019s no law whatsoever\" that requires him to provide Congress his tax returns. While there is no law requiring Trump to publicly release his tax returns, federal law of [[Internal Revenue Code|IRS Code]] section 6103(f) does require Trump's (or anyone else's) tax returns to be given to Congress if they request it.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farley|first1=Robert|title=Trump Wrong About Tax Law|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2019/04/trump-wrong-about-tax-law/|website=[[FactCheck.org]]|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/6103|title=26 U.S. Code \u00a7 6103 - Confidentiality and disclosure of returns and return information|website=LII / Legal Information Institute}}</ref>\n\n====Trump's efforts in court to block House subpoenas====\n=====House Ways and Means Committee's suit to enforce subpoena to IRS=====\nOn May 17, 2019, Treasury Secretary Mnuchin again refused to hand over the records.<ref name=Defies/> On July 2, 2019, the House Committee on Ways and Means sued Mnuchin and IRS Commissioner Rettig to enforce the subpoena and obtain six years of Trump's tax returns.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/> The suit is pending before U.S. District Judge [[Trevor McFadden]], a Trump appointee, in the [[U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]].<ref name=Thomsen>Jacqueline Thomsen, [https://www.law.com/nationallawjournal/2019/09/20/the-obvious-answer-ex-house-attorneys-back-democrats-lawsuit-for-trump-tax-returns/ 'The Obvious Answer': Ex-House Attorneys Back Democrats' Lawsuit for Trump Tax Returns], ''National Law Journal'' (September 20, 2019).</ref> In September 2019, a bipartisan group of six former general counsels to the House of Representatives filed an [[amicus brief]] in the case, urging the court to reject Trump's claims that the House lacks standing to bring the case.<ref name=Thomsen/>\n\n=====''Trump v. Mazars USA, LLP'': Trump's efforts to block House Oversight Committee subpoena to accounting firm=====\n{{main|Trump v. Mazars USA, LLP}}\nOn May 20, 2019, U.S. District Judge [[Amit Mehta]] of the [[U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]], refused a request by Trump's attorneys to quash the subpoena from the House Oversight Committee directed to Trump's accounting firm, Mazars USA LLP, ruling that the subpoena must be complied with.<ref name=trumptaxloss>{{cite news|author=Jan Wolfe|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-court-mazars-idUSKCN1SQ29H|title=Trump loses lawsuit challenging subpoena for financial records|date=May 21, 2019|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=DCtDDCOversight>''[https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20190523g19 Trump v. Committee on Oversight & Reform of U.S. House of Representatives]'', 380 F. Supp. 3d 76 (D.D.C. 2019).</ref> The district court held that the subpoena was well within Congress's broad investigative powers and rejected Trump's claim that the subpoena to Mazars was \"a usurpation of an exclusively executive or judicial function.\"<ref name=DCtDDCOversight/>\n\nTrump then appealed to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia]], which heard [[oral argument]] on July 12, 2019, and then issued a ruling against Trump on October 11, 2019. In its 2&ndash;1 ruling, the court of appeals upheld the lower court's ruling, holding that \"contrary to the President's arguments, the Committee possesses authority under both the House Rules and the Constitution to issue the subpoena\" for eight years of tax returns to Mazars, and that Mazars therefore \"must comply\" with the subpoena.<ref name=FahrentholdDCCir>David A. Fahrenthold, Spencer S. Hsu & Ann E. Marimow, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/legal-issues/appeals-court-rules-against-trump-in-fight-with-congress-over-presidents-accounting-firm-records/2019/10/11/42933894-b9ea-11e9-b3b4-2bb69e8c4e39_story.html Appeals court rules against Trump in fight with Congress over president\u2019s accounting firm records], ''Washington Post'' (October 11, 2019).</ref><ref name=Hemel>Daniel Hemel, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/10/14/how-trump-can-put-off-his-tax-return-case-until-after-election/ How Trump can put off his tax return case until after the election], ''Washington Post'' (October 14, 2019).</ref> The 66-page majority opinion was written by Judge [[David S. Tatel]], joined by [[Patricia A. Millett]]; Judge [[Neomi Rao]], a Trump appointee, dissented.<ref name=FahrentholdDCCir/> Trump's motion for rehearing ''[[en banc]]'' (i.e., before the entire D.C. Circuit) was denied on November 13, 2019, on an 8&ndash;3 vote.<ref name=Marimow>Ann E. Marimow, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/legal-issues/congress-can-seek-eight-years-of-trumps-tax-records-appeals-court-rules/2019/11/13/b4fc8002-fc07-11e9-8906-ab6b60de9124_story.html Congress can have access to eight years of Trump's tax records, appeals court orders], ''Washington Post'' (November 13, 2019).</ref><ref>''[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/6548874/Mazars-20191113.pdf Trump v. Mazars USA LLP]'' denial of rehearing ''en banc'', No. 19-5142 (D.C. Cir. Nov. 13, 2019).</ref> The ruling was the second appeals court decision within ten days against Trump regarding release of his tax returns.<ref name=Marimow/> \n\nTrump subsequently filed a petition for a [[writ of certiorari]] to the Supreme Court of the United States, asking the Court to review the case.  On December 13, 2019, the Supreme Court decided to review both the ''Trump v. Mazars US, LLP'' case (Supreme Court No. 19-715) and the ''Trump v. Deutsche Bank AG'' case (Supreme Court number 19-760). The court consolidated both cases and indicated that the cases would be set for [[oral argument]] sometime in the March 2020 argument session.<ref name=LiptakCertGranted>Adam Liptak, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/13/us/supreme-court-trump-financial-records.html Supreme Court to Rule on Release of Trump's Financial Records], ''New York Times'' (December 13, 2019).</ref><ref name=OrdersList>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/121319zr_1a7d.pdf Order List: December 13, 2019], Supreme Court of the United States.</ref> The Second Circuit's [[Appellate procedure in the United States|mandate]] was stayed pending the Supreme Court's decision in the case.<ref name=OrdersList/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/18/us/politics/trump-supreme-court-tax-returns.html|title=Chief Justice Gives Trump Temporary Reprieve in Financial Records Case|first=Adam|last=Liptak|date=November 18, 2019|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> The Court's decision in the case is believed to be a likely [[landmark ruling]] on how far presidents may resist subpoenas or other demands for information from the Congress and from prosecutors.<ref name=LiptakCertGranted/>\n\n===California primary election law===\nOn July 30, 2019, California governor [[Gavin Newsom]] signed the Presidential Tax Transparency and Accountability Act (S.B. 27), a law requiring candidates for president and California governor, as a condition for gaining California [[ballot access]], to release their most recent five years of federal tax returns at least 98 days ahead of the primary election (which would be November 26, 2019, for the 2020 primaries, since the California primary is on March 3, 2020).<ref name=BeckerSullivan>Stephanie Becker & Kate Sullivan, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/21/politics/california-tax-returns-trump/index.html California Supreme Court says law requiring presidential candidates to turn over tax returns is invalid], CNN (November 21, 2019).</ref><ref name=\"nytimes-30jul2019\">{{cite news|last1=Medina|first1=Jennifer|last2=Karni|first2=Annie|title=California Requires Trump Tax Returns Under New Election Law|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/30/us/politics/california-trump-tax-returns.html|access-date=July 30, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-30jul2019\">{{cite news|title=California governor signs law that would require Trump to release tax returns|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jul/30/california-governor-signs-law-that-would-require-trump-to-release-tax-returns|access-date=July 30, 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTrump immediately sued the State of California, seeking to block implementation of the law, asserting that the law is unconstitutional.<ref name=CalInjunction>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-09-19/trump-tax-returns-federal-court-challenge-california|title=Federal judge blocks California law to force disclosure of Trump's tax returns|date=September 19, 2019|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|author=John Myers}}</ref> On September 19, 2019, U.S. District Judge [[Morrison C. England]] issued a temporary injunction blocking the law from taking effect.<ref name=CalInjunction/> California appealed; [[California Secretary of State]] [[Alex Padilla]] said: \"Our elected leaders have a legal and moral obligation to be transparent with voters about potential conflicts of interest. This law is fundamental to preserving and protecting American democracy.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=John Myers|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-10-01/california-appeal-judge-trump-tax-returns|title=California will appeal judge's decision to block law requiring Trump's tax returns|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] dismissed California's appeal of the federal district court decision as [[Mootness|moot]], in light of the California Supreme Court's decision (see below).<ref>Daniel Tay, [https://www.law360.com/articles/1229287/9th-circ-tosses-suits-on-calif-s-invalidated-tax-return-law 9th Circ. Tosses Suits On Calif.'s Invalidated Tax Return Law], ''[[Law360]]'' (December 17, 2019).</ref>\n\nThe law was separately challenged in state court, and in November 2019, the [[California Supreme Court]] unanimously invalidated the law, meaning that Trump will not have to release his tax returns to get on the primary ballot in California in 2020.<ref name=BeckerSullivan/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article237248624.html|title=California can\u2019t force Donald Trump to release tax returns, state Supreme Court rules|last=Anderson|first=Bryan|date=November 21, 2019|website=The Sacramento Bee|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> Chief Justice [[Tani Gorre Cantil-Sakauye]] wrote that \"The Legislature may well be correct that a presidential candidate's income tax returns could provide California voters with important information\" but that the requirement to release the returns conflicted with the [[California Constitution]]'s \"specification of an inclusive open presidential primary ballot.\"<ref name=BeckerSullivan/>\n\n===New York TRUST Act===\nIn May 2019, the [[New York State Senate]] passed the TRUST Act which would amend state law to permit the commissioner of [[New York State Department of Taxation and Finance|the state Department of Taxation and Finance]] to release any state tax return requested by the leaders of the [[House Ways and Means Committee]], the [[Senate Finance Committee]] or the [[Joint Committee on Taxation]] for any \"specific and legitimate legislative purpose.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/ny-state-senate-passes-bill-allowing-congress-get-trump-tax-n1003396|title=N.Y. state Senate passes bill allowing Congress to get Trump tax returns; The state Senate also passed legislation that would make it easier for the state to prosecute individuals who were pardoned by the president.|author=Allan Smith|date=May 8, 2019|publisher=NBC News|access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/new-york-senate-passes-bill-to-let-congress-see-president-trumps-state-tax-returns|title=New York Senate Passes Bill to Let Congress See President Trump's State Tax Returns|author=Matt Naham|date=May 8, 2019|website=LawAndCrime.com|access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref> The [[New York State Assembly]] approved the bill on May 22, sending it to the governor.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/22/nyregion/trump-state-tax-returns.html|title=New York Passes Bill Giving Congress a Way to Get Trump's State Tax Returns|first=Jesse|last=McKinley|date=May 22, 2019|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> On July 8 [[List of governors of New York|Gov.]] [[Andrew M. Cuomo]] signed the bill.<ref name=\"McKinley2019\"/> \n\nTrump sued the State and the House Ways and Means Committee fifteen days later to block release of the tax returns.<ref name=\"TrumpSuitNY\"/> In November 2019, Trump's suit was dismissed on [[personal jurisdiction]] grounds.<ref name=\"Polantz\"/>\n\n===''Trump v. Vance'': Trump's challenge to Manhattan district attorney subpoena===\nIn late August 2019,<ref name=TurnOver/> soon after opening an investigation into [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal|hush-money payments to Stormy Daniels]], the [[New York County District Attorney|Manhattan district attorney's office]] issued a subpoena to Trump's accounting firm, [[Mazars|Mazars USA]], for eight years of Trump's individual tax returns and corporate tax records for the Trump Organization.<ref name=TurnOver/><ref name=EightYearsSubpoenaed>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/16/nyregion/trump-tax-returns-cy-vance.html|title=8 Years of Trump Tax Returns Are Subpoenaed by Manhattan D.A.|last1=Rashbaum|first1=William K.|last2=Protess|first2=Ben|date=September 16, 2019|work=New York Times|access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref> The existence of the subpoena was first reported by the ''New York Times'' in September 2019.<ref name=EightYearsSubpoenaed/>\n\nTrump sought to quash the subpoena in [[United States federal court|federal court]], contending that a sitting president enjoys \"absolute immunity from criminal process of any kind.\"<ref name=TurnOver/> In court filings in September 2019, New York prosecutors rejected Trump's claim that he has \"sweeping immunity\" from a criminal probe while he is in office, writing that Trump was \"seeking to invent and enforce a new presidential 'tax return privilege,' on the theory that disclosing information in a tax return will necessarily reveal information that will somehow impede the functioning of a President, sufficiently to meet the test of irreparable harm.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/23/new-york-trump-tax-returns-1763041|title=New York prosecutors reject Trump's immunity claim in tax returns case|author=Toby Ecker|date=September 23, 2019|website=politico.com|access-date=September 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/fadec6510fc543e497d594c0db8ecd10|title=Prosecutor says Trump wants 'sweeping immunity' in tax fight|author=Larry Neumeister|date=September 23, 2019|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nOn October 7, 2019, Judge [[Victor Marrero]] of the [[U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York]] rejected Trump's effort to prevent his tax returns from being turned over to the New York grand jury, and ordered Trump to comply with a subpoena. In a 75-page opinion, the court called Trump's contention an overreach of executive power that is \"repugnant to the nation's governmental structure and constitutional values.\"<ref name=TurnOver/><ref name=SDNYDecision/> Enforcement of the subpoena was temporarily delayed pending consideration by the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]].<ref name=TurnOver/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/07/politics/trump-tax-returns-lawsuit/index.html|title=Judge dismisses Trump request to keep taxes secret in New York|last=Orden|first=Erica|publisher=CNN|date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> Later the same month, [[oral argument]] before the Second Circuit took place before a three-judge panel of Chief Judge [[Robert A. Katzmann]], Judge [[Denny Chin]], and Judge [[Christopher F. Droney]]. Trump's private lawyer, William S. Consovoy, argued that a president enjoyed absolute \"presidential immunity\" from all investigation and criminal process while in office; responding to a hypothetical from the court, Consovoy said the president should be shielded even if he hypothetically committed murder on [[Fifth Avenue]] in Manhattan.<ref name=ImmunityClaim>Ann E. Marimow & Jonathan O'Connell, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/legal-issues/ny-based-appeals-court-to-decide-whether-manhattan-da-can-get-trumps-tax-returns/2019/10/22/8c491346-ef6e-11e9-8693-f487e46784aa_story.html Trump lawyer argues a sitting president would be immune from prosecution even if he were to shoot someone], ''Washington Post'' (October 22, 2019).</ref><ref>Lauren Aratani, [https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/23/donald-trump-immune-shoot-fifth-avenue-murder Trump couldn't be prosecuted if he shot someone on Fifth Avenue, lawyer claims], ''The Guardian'' (October 23, 2019).</ref><ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?465172-1/circuit-hears-oral-argument-president-trumps-tax-returns-audio-only&live Oral argument audiorecording and transcript], ''Trump v. Vance'', [[C-SPAN]], October 23, 2019</ref> In response, counsel for the Manhattan District Attorney's Office told the court that \"there is no such thing as presidential immunity for tax returns\" and noted that tax returns are frequently subpoenaed in financial investigations.<ref name=ImmunityClaim/>\n\nOn November 4, 2019, a three-judge panel of the Second Circuit unanimously ruled that Mazars must comply with the subpoena and hand over eight years of Trump's tax returns.<ref name=WeiserLiptak/><ref name=2dCir/> The court held that the president is not immune from \"the enforcement of a state grand jury subpoena directing a third party to produce non-privileged material, even when the subject matter under investigation pertains to the President\" and that a state grand jury may permissibly issue subpoenas \"in aid of its investigation of potential crimes committed by persons within its jurisdiction, even if that investigation may in some way implicate the President.\"<ref name=2dCir/> Noting that \"the President concedes that his immunity lasts only so long as he holds office and that he could therefore be prosecuted after leaving office,\" the Second Circuit ruled that there \"is no obvious reason why a state could not begin to investigate a President during his term and, with the information secured during that search, ultimately determine to prosecute him after he leaves office.\"<ref name=2dCir/> \n\nTrump subsequently filed a petition for a [[writ of certiorari]] to the Supreme Court, asserting that the grand-jury subpoena directed to him violates [[Article II of the United States Constitution|Article II]] and the [[Supremacy Clause]] of the Constitution. In December 2019, the Court agreed to hear the appeal, and initially set [[oral arguments]] for March 2020.<ref name=VanceDocket>[https://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/trump-v-vance/ Case Files: ''Trump v. Vance''] (S. Ct. No. 19-635), [[SCOTUSblog]].</ref> However, the Supreme Court indefinitely postponed oral argument in the case due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].<ref>Joan Biskupic, [https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/03/politics/supreme-court-trump-documents-coronavirus/index.html Delay in Trump's financial documents cases clouds House power on investigations], CNN (April 3, 2090).</ref>\n\n===Whistleblower complaint regarding interference in mandatory IRS audit process===\nOn July 29, 2019, a career IRS official filed a whistleblower complaint with the [[House Ways and Means Committee]], [[United States Senate Committee on Finance|Senate Finance Committee]], and [[Treasury Inspector General for Tax Administration]], stating that at least one [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department]] official had inappropriately interfered in the audit process for the tax returns of the president and vice president,<ref name=SteinHamburgerDawsey>{{cite news|author1=Jeff Stein|author2=Tom Hamburger|author3=Josh Dawsey|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/irs-whistleblower-said-to-report-treasury-political-appointee-might-have-tried-to-interfere-in-audit-of-trump-or-pence/2019/10/03/0c768b34-e52e-11e9-a331-2df12d56a80b_story.html|title=IRS whistleblower said to report Treasury political appointee might have tried to interfere in audit of Trump or Pence|work=The Washington Post|date=October 3, 2019}}</ref> which takes place annually in accordance with IRS policy.<ref>{{cite news|author=Naomi Jagoda|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/464469-tax-return-whistleblower-in-spotlight-amid-impeachment-fight|title=Tax-return whistleblower in spotlight amid impeachment fight|work=The Hill|date=October 6, 2019}}</ref> The possibility that political appointees interfered with audits conducted by career civil servants alarmed former IRS officials and legal experts.<ref name=SteinHamburgerDawsey/> Due to stringent laws regarding disclosure of tax information, the details of the complaint have not been made public.<ref name=SteinHamburgerDawsey/> However, Representative [[Richard E. Neal]], the Democratic chair of the House Ways and Means Committee, said in September 2019 that he was consulting legal counsel on whether the whistleblower's complaint could be publicly released.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jeff Stein|author2=Tom Hamburger|author3=Josh Dawsey|author4=Colin Wilhelm|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-27/democrat-weighs-releasing-complaint-about-irs-trump-tax-audit|title=Democrat Weighs Releasing Complaint About IRS Trump Tax Audit|work=Bloomberg|date=September 27, 2019}}.</ref>\n\nThe whistleblower's report was referred to by Neal and other House Democrats in the federal lawsuit regarding Trump's refusal to comply with a House Ways and Means Committee subpoena for the returns; in a filing, Neal wrote that the whistleblower's complaint presents credible evidence of \"potential 'inappropriate efforts to influence' the mandatory audit program\" and raises \"serious and urgent concerns,\" thereby bolsters the committee's case for obtaining the tax returns.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lorenzo|first1=Aaron|title=House Democrats say bolsters case for getting Trump's tax returns|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/20/tax-democrats-trump-1673427|access-date=October 1, 2019|work=[[Politico]]|date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019)]]\n*[[Wealth of Donald Trump]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Donald Trump}}\n{{Trump businesses}}\n[[Category:Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:United States tax law]]\n[[Category:Controversies of the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump controversies|Tax returns]]\n", "text_old": "{{Donald Trump series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\nThe '''tax returns of Donald Trump''' have been the subject of controversy for the past several years, particularly over their not having been made public despite his political career.\n\nBefore Trump announced his candidacy for president, he repeatedly promised to release his tax returns, making such pledges in 2011, 2014 (\"absolutely\") and 2015.<ref name=\"FactPence\"/><ref name=\"Harwell\"/> During [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|his presidential campaign]], Trump first said he would release his returns after they were \"worked on.\u201d<ref name=fivetimes/> Then Trump claimed<!-- Since no evidence has ever been presented that this is true, using \"claimed\" is justified. --> that, because the returns were being audited, he could not make them public, but would do so. No law actually prevents tax returns from being released due to an audit, as emphasized by the [[Commissioner of Internal Revenue|commissioner of internal revenue]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davison|first1=Laura|last2=Talev|first2=Margaret|title=Trump Falsely Says Law Prevents Him Releasing Tax Returns Under Audit|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-05/trump-refutes-democrats-authority-to-obtain-his-tax-returns|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Orion|last1=Rummler|title=IRS commissioner: No rule against releasing Trump's tax returns while under audit|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-tax-returns-irs-commissioner-audit-20ebb0a7-dc47-4177-bf4c-565aa5cfb734.html|date=10 April 2019|website=[[Axios.com]]|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref> Trump later said that voters were not interested in his returns; that \"there's nothing to learn from them\"; and that his tax rate is \"none of your business\".<ref name=\"Harwell\"/>\n\nSince Trump's election, he has refused requests to release the returns, making him one of the few presidents in recent times to not reveal their tax returns. Trump was the first major party nominee since 1976 not to make his tax returns public. Several states have proposed bills that would require presidential candidates to release their tax returns in order to be listed on the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 ballot]]; such a bill was passed by the [[California Legislature]] and signed by Democratic Governor [[Gavin Newsom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/california/story/2019/07/30/californias-newsom-signs-bill-to-force-trump-tax-returns-1122154|title=California's Newsom signs bill to force Trump tax returns|last=White|first=Jeremy|date=July 30, 2019|work=Politico|access-date=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Ways and Means Committee]] of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] made a formal request to the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS), and later issued a [[subpoena]] to the IRS, for six years of Trump's returns, as part of an effort by the committee to evaluate \"the extent to which the I.R.S. audits and enforces the federal tax laws against a president.\"<ref name=WaysMeansSub>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/10/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-subpoena.html|title=House Ways and Means Chairman Subpoenas Trump Tax Returns|first=Nicholas|last=Fandos|date=May 10, 2019|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]] defied the subpoena.<ref name=UPIfinal>{{cite web|last1=Uria|first1=Daniel|title=Mnuchin: Treasury to make 'final decision' on Trump tax returns May 6|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2019/04/23/Mnuchin-Treasury-to-make-final-decision-on-Trump-tax-returns-May-6/8181556063426/|publisher=[[United Press International]]|access-date=April 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rappeport|first1=Alan|title=Steven Mnuchin Refuses to Release Trump's Tax Returns to Congress|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/06/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-mnuchin.html|website=The New York Times|access-date=7 May 2019|date=6 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/10/us/politics/democrats-trump-tax-returns.html|title=House Ways and Means Chairman Subpoenas Trump Tax Records|first=Nicholas|last=Fandos|date=May 10, 2019|website=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mnuchin-defies-subpoena-for-president-trumps-tax-returns-11558123367|title=Mnuchin Defies Subpoena for President Trump's Tax Returns|first=Richard|last=Rubin|date=May 17, 2019|newspaper=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> Upon the Trump administration's refusal to turn over the documents, the Ways and Means Committee filed a suit to enforce the subpoena.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/02/738030272/house-democrats-sue-for-trumps-tax-returns|title=House Democrats Sue For Trump's Tax Returns|author=Kelsey Snell|date=July 2, 2019|website=NPR|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">Quinta Jurecic, [https://www.lawfareblog.com/house-ways-and-means-committee-sues-trump-tax-returns House Ways and Means Committee Sues for Trump Tax Returns], ''Lawfare'' (July 2, 2019).</ref> That case is pending.<ref name=Thomsen/> A draft IRS legal memo, written in fall 2018 and reported in May 2019, concluded that the IRS must provide the requested tax returns to Congress unless Trump invokes executive privilege, contradicting the administration's justification for defying the earlier subpoena.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/confidential-draft-irs-memo-says-tax-returns-must-be-given-to-congress-unless-president-invokes-executive-privilege/2019/05/21/8ed41834-7b1c-11e9-8bb7-0fc796cf2ec0_story.html|title=Confidential draft IRS memo says tax returns must be given to Congress unless president invokes executive privilege|newspaper=Washington Post|date=May 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeparately, the [[House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight Committee]] issued a subpoena to Trump's accounting firm for tax records and other records, as part of the committee's investigation into (1) whether Trump \"may have engaged in illegal conduct before and during his tenure in office\"; (2) whether Trump \"has undisclosed [[conflicts of interest]] that may impair his ability to make impartial policy decisions\"; (3) whether Trump was complying with the Constitution's [[Foreign Emoluments Clause]] and [[Domestic Emoluments Clause]]; and (4) whether Trump \"has accurately reported his finances to the Office of Government Ethics and other federal entities.\"<ref name=DCCirDecision/> Trump sued to block the subpoena; the [[U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]], and later the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia]], rejected Trump's position and have held that the subpoena must be complied with.<ref name=DCtDDCOversight/><ref name=FahrentholdDCCir/><ref name=Hemel/>\n\nIn late August 2019, the Office of the [[New York County District Attorney]] issued a subpoena to Trump seeking eight years of his personal and corporate tax returns, as part of state prosecutors' investigation into [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal|hush-money payments made during the 2016 presidential election campaign]].<ref name=TurnOver>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/07/nyregion/trump-taxes-lawsuit-vance.html|title=Trump Taxes: President Ordered to Turn Over Returns to Manhattan D.A.|last=Rashbaum|first=Weiser|website=The New York Times|date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> Trump sought to quash the subpoena, contending that a sitting president enjoys \"absolute immunity from criminal process of any kind.\"<ref name=TurnOver/> In October 2019, Judge [[Victor Marrero]] of the [[U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York]] rejected Trump's effort to prevent his tax returns from being turned over to the New York grand jury, and ordered Trump to comply with a subpoena. In a 75-page opinion, the court called Trump's contention an overreach of executive power that is \"repugnant to the nation's governmental structure and constitutional values.\"<ref name=TurnOver/><ref name=SDNYDecision>{{cite court|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/07/politics/sdny-ruling-trump-tax-returns/index.html|litigants=Trump v. Vance|vol=395|reporter=F. Supp. 3d.|page=283|opinion=court=S.D.N.Y.}}</ref> The [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] upheld the lower court's ruling in November 2019, rejecting Trump's claim that presidents are immune from state grand jury subpoenas.<ref name=WeiserLiptak>Benjamin Weiser & Adam Liptak, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/04/nyregion/trump-taxes-vance-appeal.html Trump Taxes: Appeals Court Rules President Must Turn Over 8 Years of Tax Returns], ''New York Times'' (November 4, 2019).</ref><ref name=2dCir>''[https://int.nyt.com/data/documenthelper/6407-trump-vance-appeal/a0279d1a81a92e6abce8/optimized/full.pdf#page=1 Trump v. Vance]'' (2d Cir. Nov. 4, 2019).</ref>\n\nSeparately, a [[New York law|New York state law]] was enacted in July 2019, authorizing New York state tax officials to release state tax returns, including Trump's, for any \"specified and legitimate legislative purpose\" to the House Ways and Means Committee and three other congressional committees.<ref name=\"McKinley2019\">{{cite news|last1=McKinley|first1=Jesse|last2=Fandos|first2=Nicholas|title=Cuomo Signs a Bill to Allow Release of Trump's State Tax Returns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/08/nyregion/trump-ny-taxes-cuomo.html|work=The New York Times|date=8 July 2019}}</ref> Trump sued the State and the House Ways and Means Committee fifteen days later to block release of the tax returns.<ref name=\"TrumpSuitNY\">{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/23/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-new-york.html|title=Trump Sues New York and Congress to Shield His State Tax Returns|first1=Nicholas|last1=Fandos|first2=Jesse|last2=McKinley|date=July 23, 2019|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> In November 2019, Trump's suit was dismissed on jurisdictional grounds.<ref name=\"Polantz\">Katelyn Polantz, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/11/politics/donald-trump-tax-returns/index.html Trump can't sue New York state in DC federal court to stop release of tax returns, judge says], CNN (November 11, 2019).</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe IRS has stated that nothing prevents an individual from releasing their tax returns; an audit cannot stop the tax return release, and several former leaders of IRS have said that audits are a poor reason to justify not releasing tax returns. In any case, Trump has the ability to put on hold a current audit. Before Trump's election, every elected president from [[Richard Nixon]] onward has released their tax returns annually. While president, Nixon himself released his tax returns despite them being under audit. Also, all major presidential nominees from 1976 onward released their tax returns.<ref name=WaPoBus/>\n\n==Tax figures from 1985 through 1994==\nTrump lost $1.17 billion between 1985 and 1994 according to 10 years of Trump's tax information obtained by the ''New York Times'', with the amount more than \"nearly any other individual American taxpayer\" during that period. Although Trump has acknowledged the tax-advantaged nature of the real estate business due to large depreciation write-offs to generate losses and reduce tax liabilities, the ''Times'' reported \"depreciation cannot account for the hundreds of millions of dollars in losses.\"<ref name=\"Red\">{{cite news|last1=Buettner|first1=Russ|last2=Craig|first2=Susanne|title=Decade in the Red: Trump Tax Figures Show Over $1 Billion in Business Losses|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/07/us/politics/donald-trump-taxes.html|access-date=May 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|date=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/07/us/trump-tax-figures.html|title=5 Takeaways From 10 Years of Trump Tax Figures|last1=Buettner|first1=Russ|last2=Craig|first2=Susanne|date=May 7, 2019|website=The New York Times|access-date=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/08/trump-defends-tax-tactics-after-nyt-story-says-he-racked-up-more-than-1-billion-in-losses-it-was-sport.html|title=Trump defends tax tactics after NYT probe says he racked up more than $1 billion in losses: 'It was sport'|last=Calia|first=Mike|date=May 8, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=May 8, 2019}}</ref> Due to losing more than $500 million in combined losses, section 172 of the [[Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993]] gave Trump $915.7 million in tax exemption, which he used to pay off 8 years of taxes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/07/us/trump-tax-figures.html|title=5 Takeaways From 10 Years of Trump Tax Figures|last1=Craig|first1=Susanne|last2=Buettner|first2=Russ|date=May 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/103rd-congress/house-bill/2264/text|title=Text - H.R.2264 - 103rd Congress (1993-1994): Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993|last=Sabo|first=Martin Olav|date=August 10, 1993|publisher=[[Congress.gov]]|access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trumps-early-financial-losses-were-so-steep-that-he-did-not-pay-income-taxes-for-eight-years-according-to-new-report/2019/05/07/cb019e4a-7120-11e9-8be0-ca575670e91c_story.html|title=Trump's early financial losses were so steep that he did not pay income taxes for eight years, according to new report|last=Fahrenthold|first=David A.|date=May 5, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Partially leaked returns of 1995 and 2005==\nParts of Trump's 1995 and 2005 tax returns have been leaked.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-times-trump-declared-a-916-million-loss-in-1995-tax-returns/|title=Trump incurrs $916 million loss on his income tax returns|last=Doe|first=John|date=October 1, 2016|work=CBS News|access-date=October 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002062654/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-times-trump-declared-a-916-million-loss-in-1995-tax-returns/|archive-date=October 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trumps-tax-return-leaked-rachel-maddow-what-accountants-think-alternative-minimum-tax/|title=A Trump tax return revealed -- here's what accountants think of it|website=cbsnews.com|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929010525/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trumps-tax-return-leaked-rachel-maddow-what-accountants-think-alternative-minimum-tax/|archive-date=September 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published some tax documents from 1995. ''The New York Times'' reported that the ''Times'' had been given three pages of certain state tax returns for Trump for the year 1995. The materials indicated that Trump incurred a $916 million [[net operating loss]] which, for Federal income tax purposes, could have prevented Trump from owing any Federal income taxes for up to 18 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-times-trump-declared-a-916-million-loss-in-1995-tax-returns/|title=Trump incurrs $916 million loss on his income tax returns|last=Doe|first=John|date=October 1, 2016|publisher=CBS News|access-date=October 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002062654/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-times-trump-declared-a-916-million-loss-in-1995-tax-returns/|archive-date=October 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Marc Kasowitz]] of [[Kasowitz, Benson, Torres & Friedman]] wrote to the ''Times'' stating, according to one report, that \"the publication of Trump's tax records was illegal because Trump had not authorized their disclosure ... [and] threatening 'prompt initiation of appropriate legal action.'\"<ref>Zaretsky, Staci, [http://abovethelaw.com/2016/10/donald-trump-chooses-biglaw-firm-to-fight-new-york-times-over-publication-of-tax-documents/ \"Donald Trump Chooses Biglaw Firm To Fight New York Times Over Publication Of Tax Documents\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617093028/https://abovethelaw.com/2016/10/donald-trump-chooses-biglaw-firm-to-fight-new-york-times-over-publication-of-tax-documents/|date=June 17, 2018}}, ''[[Above the Law (website)|Above the Law]]'', October 3, 2016. Retrieved January 17, 2017.</ref>\n\nTrump claimed on his tax returns that he lost money, but did not recognize it in the form of canceled debts. Trump might have performed a [[Swap (finance)|stock-for-debt swap]]. This would have allowed Trump to avoid paying [[Income tax in the United States|income taxes]] for at least 18 years. An [[Income tax audit|audit]] of Trump's tax returns for 2002 through 2008 was \"closed administratively by agreement with the [[Internal Revenue Service|I.R.S.]] without assessment or payment, on a net basis, of any deficiency.\" Tax attorneys believe the government may have reduced what Trump was able to claim as a loss without requiring him to pay any additional taxes.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/11/01/a-big-dirty-secret-from-donald-trumps-tax-returns-has-been-exposed/ \"A big, dirty secret from Donald Trump's tax returns has been exposed\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210192856/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/11/01/a-big-dirty-secret-from-donald-trumps-tax-returns-has-been-exposed/|date=February 10, 2019}}. ''The Washington Post''. November 1, 2016. Retrieved November 2, 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/04/us/politics/donald-trump-taxes.html \"How a Simple Tax Rule Let Donald Trump Turn a $916 Million Loss Into a Plus\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209120846/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/04/us/politics/donald-trump-taxes.html|date=December 9, 2018}}. ''The New York Times''. October 4, 2016. Retrieved November 2, 2016.</ref> It is unknown whether the I.R.S. challenged Trump's use of the swaps because he has not released his tax returns. Trump's lawyers advised against Trump using the equity for debt swap, as they believed it to be potentially illegal.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/02/opinion/avoiding-taxes-trump-style.html \"Avoiding Taxes, Trump-Style\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230939/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/02/opinion/avoiding-taxes-trump-style.html|date=December 20, 2018}}. ''The New York Times''. November 2, 2016. Retrieved November 2, 2016.</ref>\n\nOn March 14, 2017, the first two pages of Trump's 2005 federal income tax returns were leaked to [[Rachel Maddow]] and shown on [[MSNBC]]. The document states that Trump had a gross adjusted income of $150&nbsp;million and paid $38&nbsp;million in federal taxes. The White House confirmed the authenticity of these documents and claimed: \"Despite this substantial income figure and tax paid, it is totally illegal to steal and publish tax returns.\"<ref name=\"nyt-taxes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/14/us/politics/donald-trump-taxes.html|title=Trump Wrote Off $100 Million in Business Losses in 2005|last1=Baker|first1=Peter|author1-link=Peter Baker (journalist)|last2=Drucker|first2=Jesse|last3=Craig|first3=Susanne|author3-link=Susanne Craig|last4=Barstow|first4=David|author4-link=David Barstow|date=March 15, 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=March 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"hill-taxes\">{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/324016-wh-releases-trump-tax-info-ahead-of-msnbc-report-made-150m-in-2005|title=WH releases Trump tax info ahead of MSNBC report: He paid $38M in federal taxes in '05|last=Jagoda|first=Naomi|access-date=March 15, 2017|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref>.\n\n==Before his presidency==\n{{further|Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nIn 1999, while Trump was considering whether [[Donald Trump 2000 presidential campaign|to run for president]] under the [[Reform Party of the United States of America|Reform Party]], he said \"probably wouldn't have a problem with\" releasing his tax returns if he ran.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kaczynski|first1=Andrew|title=Trump In 1999: I Probably Wouldn't Have A Problem Releasing My Tax Returns If I Ran|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/andrewkaczynski/during-1999-run-trump-vowed-to-release-his-tax-returns|website=[[Buzzfeed News]]|access-date=August 7, 2019|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, Trump said that when President [[Barack Obama]] produces \"[[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|his birth certificate]] ... I\u2019d love to give my tax returns\". [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories#Long form, 2011|Obama's birth certificate was released a week later]], resulting in Trump saying his tax returns would be released \"at the appropriate time\".<ref name=\"FactPence\">{{cite web|last1=Qiu|first1=Linda|title=Pence's False claim that Trump 'hasn't broken' tax return promise|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/oct/05/mike-pence/pences-false-claim-trump-hasnt-broken-tax-return-p/|publisher=[[Politifact]]|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Trump implored for Republican presidential candidate Mitt Romney's tax returns to be released on April 1, which \"historically is the time that everybody gives them\".<ref name=\"WaPoBus\">{{cite web|last1=Harwell|first1=Drew|title=All the excuses Trump has given for why he won't release his tax returns|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2016/09/15/a-running-tally-of-trumps-many-excuses-for-why-he-wont-release-his-tax-returns/|website=[[Washington Post]]|access-date=August 7, 2019|date=September 15, 2016}}</ref> That year, Trump also said that not seeing a presidential candidate's tax returns would lead people to think there was \"almost, like, something wrong. What's wrong?\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Kelly|first=Nora|title=How Hillary Clinton Is Using Her Taxes as a Political Weapon|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/08/clinton-tax-returns-trump/495755/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=August 7, 2019|date=August 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Trump's former political adviser [[Sam Nunberg]] said in 2013 and 2014 that Trump had considered the possibility of releasing his tax returns as part of a presidential campaign, believing that showing how little he paid in taxes would make him appear to be a savvy businessman.<ref name=Ward>[[Vicky Ward]], [https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/14/politics/trump-originally-wanted-to-release-tax-returns/index.html Trump wanted to release his taxes in 2013 to show how smart he was for paying so little], CNN (October 14, 2019).</ref> Nunberg said by November 2014, he had persuaded Trump to reverse course and withhold his tax returns, as Trump decided that he \"wanted to look rich rather than smart.\"<ref name=Ward/> In May 2014, Trump said in an interview: \"If I decide to run for office, I\u2019ll produce my tax returns, absolutely and I would love to do that.\"<ref name=\"FactPence\"/>\n\nIn February 2015, Trump said that if he ran for the presidency: \"I would release tax returns\".<ref name=\"FactPence\"/> On another occasion that month, he declared: \"I have no objection to certainly showing tax returns\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gass|first1=Nick|title=Carson: Trump will release tax returns before election|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/trump-release-tax-records-222887|website=[[Politico]]|access-date=August 7, 2019|date=June 5, 2016}}</ref> Later in February 2015, Trump warned: \"I will tell you upfront ... I want to pay as little taxes as I can as a private person\".<ref name=\"FactPence\"/> In May 2016, Trump voiced similar sentiments, stating he tries \"very hard to pay as little tax as possible\". However, Trump has in 2015 criticized corporate executives and \"hedge fund guys\" for paying zero or negligible taxes. He also alleged in 2011 and 2012 that half of all Americans do not pay income taxes, stating: \"it's a problem\", while noting \"crippling\" government debt. Trump also in 2012 criticized President Barack Obama for \"only\" paying a tax rate of around 20%.<ref name=WaPoBus/> Trump announced his candidacy for President in June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Santucci|first1=John|last2=Stracqualursi|first2=Veronica|title=Donald Trump Announces 2016 Presidential Campaign: 'We Are Going Make our Country Great Again'|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trump-announces-2016-presidential-campaign-make-country/story?id=31799741|work=[[ABC News]]|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Trump was asked by [[Chuck Todd]] if he would release his tax returns, to which Trump answered: \"we'll be working that over in the next period of time, Chuck. Absolutely. [...] at the appropriate time, you'll be very satisfied.\"<ref name=fivetimes>{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=5 things Donald Trump promised he'd do, but hasn't|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/12/13/5-things-donald-trump-promised-hed-do-but-hasnt/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref> In February 2016, Trump said that he would release his tax returns \"[p]robably over the next few months. They\u2019re being worked on now.\"<ref name=fivetimes/> Later that month, Trump said that he could not release his tax returns because he was under audit.<ref name=\"POLITICOtwelve\">{{cite web|last1=Becker|first1=Bernie|last2=Faler|first2=Brian|title=IRS chief: 'Rare' for taxpayer to be audited several years in a row, as Trump claims|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/02/donald-trump-irs-audit-experts-219889|publisher=[[Politico]]|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref> Trump has elaborated that he has been audited for a consecutive \"twelve years or something like that.\"<ref name=\"POLITICOtwelve\"/> In 2016, Trump's tax attorneys have stated that Trump has been under audit since 2002. However, in 2011, 2014, and 2015, Trump made offers to release his tax returns, presumably while he was still under audit.<ref name=\"FactPence\"/>\n\nThe IRS commissioner at the time, [[John Koskinen]], said that an IRS audit does not prevent the taxpayer from releasing tax returns. Koskinen also said that it \"would be rare for anyone to be audited every year\", and that if a past audit revealed no problems, \"it\u2019s a number of years \u2014 two or three at least\" before the IRS would conduct an audit again.<ref name=POLITICOtwelve/><ref name=\"POLITICOtwelve\"/>\n\nThere is no requirement that presidential candidates release their tax returns but candidates are legally free to do so even when under audit.<ref name=release>{{cite news|author=Alan Rappeport|url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/05/11/donald-trump-breaks-with-recent-history-by-not-releasing-tax-returns/|title=Donald Trump Breaks With Recent History by Not Releasing Tax Returns|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106222213/https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/05/11/donald-trump-breaks-with-recent-history-by-not-releasing-tax-returns/|archive-date=January 6, 2019|work=The New York Times|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Stockman>{{cite news|url=http://lawnewz.com/politics/legal-experts-side-with-trump-it-would-be-totally-stupid-to-release-his-taxes-during-audit/|title=Legal Experts Side With Trump; It Would Be Crazy to Release His Taxes During Audit|last=Stockman|first=Rachel|date=May 13, 2016|work=Law Newz|access-date=July 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716130007/http://lawnewz.com/politics/legal-experts-side-with-trump-it-would-be-totally-stupid-to-release-his-taxes-during-audit/|archive-date=July 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Tax lawyers differ as to whether releasing tax returns is legally advisable for someone like Trump who has stated he is under audit.<ref name=Stockman /><ref>Stewart, Emily. [https://www.thestreet.com/story/13687015/1/would-no-tax-lawyer-advise-trump-release-his-tax-returns-it-s-complicated.html \"Would No Tax Lawyer Advise Trump Release His Tax Returns? It's Complicated\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924183723/https://www.thestreet.com/story/13687015/1/would-no-tax-lawyer-advise-trump-release-his-tax-returns-it-s-complicated.html|date=September 24, 2016}}, [[TheStreet.com]] (August 27, 2016).</ref> According to [[NPR]], tax experts, such as [[New York University Law School]] professor Daniel Shaviro, say that \"Trump's lawyers may advise him not to release the returns for legal strategy purposes.\"<ref>Zarroli, Jim. [https://www.npr.org/2016/02/26/468278769/fact-check-donald-trump-cant-release-his-taxes-while-being-audited \"Fact-Check: Donald Trump Can't Release His Taxes While Being Audited?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302140445/https://www.npr.org/2016/02/26/468278769/fact-check-donald-trump-cant-release-his-taxes-while-being-audited|date=March 2, 2019}}, [[NPR]] (February 26, 2016).</ref> In contrast, economist [[Paul Krugman]] argued that Trump should be more willing to reveal his tax information if he were already under audit, as the reveal might have triggered an audit if there was not one.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/democracy-in-america/2016/06/01/the-saga-over-donald-trumps-tax-returns-rolls-on|title=The saga over Donald Trump's tax returns rolls on|date=June 1, 2016|work=The Economist|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714030549/http://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2016/06/donalds-taxes|archive-date=July 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Trump said that he did not plan to release his tax returns before the November 2016 election;<ref name=\"Rappeport\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/05/11/donald-trump-breaks-with-recent-history-by-not-releasing-tax-returns/|title=Donald Trump Breaks With Recent History by Not Releasing Tax Returns|last=Rappeport|first=Alan|date=May 11, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719083106/http://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2016/05/11/donald-trump-breaks-with-recent-history-by-not-releasing-tax-returns/|archive-date=July 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> the tax returns were not released.<ref name=MoneyWhen>{{Cite web|url=http://money.com/money/5634725/donald-trump-tax-returns-released-2019-democrats/|title=Will Donald Trump's Tax Returns Be Released? Democrats Just Made Their First Move|website=Money|language=en|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217002556/http://money.com/money/5634725/donald-trump-tax-returns-released-2019-democrats/|archive-date=February 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Trump also said in May 2016 that \"there's nothing to learn from\" his tax returns,<ref name=\"Rappeport\"/> and said on [[ABC News]] that his tax rate is \"none of your business\".<ref name=\"Harwell\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trumps-income-tax-returns-once-became-public-they-showed-he-didnt-pay-a-cent/2016/05/20/ffa2f63c-1b7c-11e6-b6e0-c53b7ef63b45_story.html|title=Trump once revealed his income tax returns. They showed he didn't pay a cent.|last=Harwell|first=Drew|date=May 21, 2016|work=The Washington Post|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706210006/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trumps-income-tax-returns-once-became-public-they-showed-he-didnt-pay-a-cent/2016/05/20/ffa2f63c-1b7c-11e6-b6e0-c53b7ef63b45_story.html|archive-date=July 6, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTrump was criticized for his refusal to release tax information. Former Republican presidential candidate [[Mitt Romney]] said, \"It is disqualifying for a modern-day presidential nominee to refuse to release tax returns to the voters.\" Romney speculated, \"There is only one logical explanation for Mr. Trump's refusal to release his returns: there is a bombshell in them.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/05/11/romney-calls-decision-by-trump-not-to-release-tax-returns-disqualifying.html|title=Romney calls decision by Trump not to release tax returns 'disqualifying'|date=May 11, 2016|work=Fox News|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619110559/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/05/11/romney-calls-decision-by-trump-not-to-release-tax-returns-disqualifying.html|archive-date=June 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[John Fund]] of the ''[[National Review]]'' said that Republican convention delegates should abstain from voting for Trump if he does not release the information, fearing that the returns could contain an electoral \"time bomb\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/435254/donald-trumps-tax-returns-delegates-should-abstain-if-he-wont-release|title=Trump's Refusal to Release Tax Returns Is a Ticking Time Bomb for the GOP|last=Fund|first=John|date=May 11, 2016|work=National Review|access-date=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718073935/http://www.nationalreview.com/article/435254/donald-trumps-tax-returns-delegates-should-abstain-if-he-wont-release|archive-date=July 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 United States presidential debates]], rival presidential candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] criticized Trump, saying that only \"a couple of years\" of Trump's tax returns were publicly available, \"and they showed he didn't pay any federal income tax\". Trump directly responded: \"That makes me smart.\" Clinton went on to suggest that Trump might not have \"paid any federal income tax for a lot of years\"; this resulted in Trump saying that the taxes he paid \"would be squandered\" by the government.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mangan|first=Dan|title=Trump brags about not paying taxes: 'That makes me smart'|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/09/26/trump-brags-about-not-paying-taxes-that-makes-me-smart.html|publisher=[[CNBC]]|access-date=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==During his presidency==\n{{further|Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency}}\n\nTrump has continued to withhold his tax returns even into his presidency as of September 2019.<ref name=MoneyWhen/>\n\nIn May 2017, Trump said that he \"might\" release his tax returns only after he had stepped down as President. This was in spite of his previous commitment made during his campaign to release his tax returns once they were not under audit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Release his tax returns after an audit is completed - Trump-O-Meter: Broken|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/promises/trumpometer/promise/1421/release-his-tax-returns-after-audit-completed/|publisher=[[Politifact]]|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Tax March protests===\n{{main|Tax March}}\nIn January 2017, an online petition on the \"We the People\" portion of the White House's website calling for the release of Trump's tax returns was set up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/01/petition-didnt-make-trump-give-tax-returns-made-listen/|title=A Petition Didn't Make Trump Give Up His Tax Returns\u2014But It Made Him Listen|last=Ellis|first=Emma Grey|newspaper=WIRED|language=en-US|date=January 26, 2017|access-date=January 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128213639/https://www.wired.com/2017/01/petition-didnt-make-trump-give-tax-returns-made-listen/|archive-date=January 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The petition gained over 1 million signatures, becoming the most signed petition on the White House's website. However, the White House gave no official response to the petition as of April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lam|first1=Bourree|title=The Fight Over Trump's Tax Returns Isn't Over|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/04/trump-tax-march/523116/|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=April 9, 2019}}</ref> Trump spokesperson [[Kellyanne Conway]] then said that \"The White House response is that he\u2019s not going to release the tax returns\" and that \"people didn't care\" about Trump's tax returns.<ref>{{cite news|last=Revesz|first=Rachel|title=Kellyanne Conway says President Trump will not release his tax returns|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/donald-trump-kellyanne-conway-tax-returns-will-not-release-under-audit-conflicts-of-interest-a7540621.html|access-date=7 October 2019|work=The Independent|date=January 22, 2017}}</ref> In response, [[Jennifer Taub]] and others planned the [[Tax March]] on April 15, 2017 ([[Tax Day]]) to demand that Trump release his tax returns;<ref>Amber Jamieson, [https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/12/tax-march-trump-tax-returns-activism-jennifer-taub Tax March: how a law professor sparked a global event to demand Trump's returns], ''The Guardian'' (April 12, 2017).</ref> tens of thousands of people marched in New York and dozens of cities across the country.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/tax-march-protests-demand-donald-trump-to-release-tax-returns/ \"Tax March\" protests demand release of Trump's tax returns], CBS News/Associated Press (April 15, 2017).</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Francescani|first1=Chris|last2=Ramstack|first2=Tom|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-taxes/thousands-at-rallies-demand-trump-release-tax-returns-idUSKBN17H0FW|title=Thousands at rallies demand Trump release tax returns|work=Reuters|date=April 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Congressional requests and subpoenas for Trump's tax returns===\nAfter winning control of the House in the [[United States House of Representatives election, 2018|2018 elections]], House Democrats signaled their intent to use their new power to demand Trump's tax returns in the new Congress, which convened in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/watch/with-house-majority-dems-intend-to-request-for-trump-s-tax-returns-1363758147582|title=With House majority, Dems intend to request Trump's tax returns|website=MSNBC.com|language=en|access-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218175948/https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/watch/with-house-majority-dems-intend-to-request-for-trump-s-tax-returns-1363758147582|archive-date=February 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/donald-trump-tax-returns-democrats-will-demand-presidents-records-house-1205085|title=Democrats set to demand Donald Trump's tax returns after winning House majority|last=Porter|first=Tom|date=November 7, 2018|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328065104/https://www.newsweek.com/donald-trump-tax-returns-democrats-will-demand-presidents-records-house-1205085|archive-date=March 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/806128/once-power-house-democrats-reportedly-demand-trumps-tax-returns|title=Once in power, House Democrats will reportedly demand Trump's tax returns|date=November 6, 2018|website=theweek.com|access-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207165348/https://theweek.com/speedreads/806128/once-power-house-democrats-reportedly-demand-trumps-tax-returns|archive-date=February 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2019, the chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means]], Congressman [[Richard Neal]], formally requested from the IRS six years of Trump's returns.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/08407f0c1bd04a2cb33842ebe8113d82|title=White House pushes back on request for Trump tax forms|first=Marcy|last=Gordon|date=April 4, 2019|agency=Associated Press|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405004721/https://apnews.com/08407f0c1bd04a2cb33842ebe8113d82|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-maneuvers-to-block-release-of-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/04/047b19e0-56f4-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|title=White House maneuvers to block release of Trump's tax returns|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405054133/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-maneuvers-to-block-release-of-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/04/047b19e0-56f4-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The last time a sitting president's tax information was requested was 45 years ago.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The request was made on April 3 via a letter to IRS Commissioner [[Charles P. Rettig]]. It requested both Trump's business and personal returns for the years 2013 through 2018. The deadline he set was April 10, seven days later.<ref name=\"auto\"/> After the first deadline was not met, Neal again wrote to Rettig on April 13, setting a second deadline of April 23, 2019, and writing that a failure to meet the deadline would be \"interpreted as a denial\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lorenzo|first1=Aaron|title=Neal gives IRS commissioner new deadline for handing over Trump's tax returns|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/04/13/irs-trump-tax-returns-1273712|publisher=[[Politico]]|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nUnder a 1924 [[Taxation in the United States|federal tax law]], \u00a7 6103 of [[title 26 of the United States Code]], Congress may request copies of anyone's tax returns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/democrats-want-use-obscure-law-grab-donald-trump-s-tax-n949286|title=Here's how Democrats plan to get Donald Trump's tax returns|website=NBC News|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190118132721/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/democrats-want-use-obscure-law-grab-donald-trump-s-tax-n949286|archive-date=January 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/olc/opinions/1977/05/31/op-olc-v001-p0085_0.pdf|title=Memorandum Opinion for the Acting Commissioner of the Internal Revenue Service - Congressional Access to Tax Returns\u201426 U.S.C. \u00a7 6103(f)|last=Harmon|first=John M.|date=May 2, 1977|website=United States Department of Justice|access-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/6103|title=26 U.S. Code \u00a7 6103 - Confidentiality and disclosure of returns and return information|website=[[Legal Information Institute]]|language=en|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401140541/https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/6103|archive-date=April 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/05/politics/trump-tax-returns/index.html|title=The 1924 law Democrats may tap to see Trump's tax returns|last=Sahadi|first=Jeanne|website=CNN|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307181133/https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/05/politics/trump-tax-returns/index.html|archive-date=March 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[treasury secretary]] is legally obliged to provide the tax returns, and there is no apparent legal mechanism to deny Congress's request.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> On April 5, 2019, Trump's personal lawyer William Consovoy wrote a letter to the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] (the parent agency of the IRS), claiming that the request for Trump's tax information is \"not consistent with governing law\" and that Congress is trying to violate Trump's [[First Amendment]] rights.<ref name=hufffight>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/trump-lawyers-fight-release-of-the-presidents-tax-returns_n_5ca7b38ce4b0dca0330159f4|title=Trump Lawyers Fight Release Of The President's Tax Returns|first1=Andy|last1=Campbell|first2=Arthur|last2=Delaney|date=April 5, 2019|website=HuffPost}}</ref>\n\n====House committees issue formal subpoenas for tax records==== \nOn April 15, 2019, the chairman of the [[House Committee on Oversight and Reform]], Representative [[Elijah Cummings]], issued a subpoena to the accounting firm Mazars USA, LLP requesting tax records and other \"financial documents concerning the President and his companies covering years both before and during his presidency.\"<ref name=DCCirDecision>''[https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=13567751942084956358 Trump v. Mazars USA]'', No. 19-5142 (D.C. Cir. Oct. 11, 2019).</ref> Cummings identified four areas that the committee aimed to investigate through the subpoena: (1) whether Trump \"may have engaged in illegal conduct before and during his tenure in office\"; (2) whether Trump \"has undisclosed [[conflicts of interest]] that may impair his ability to make impartial policy decisions\"; (3) whether Trump was complying with the Constitution's [[Foreign Emoluments Clause]] and [[Domestic Emoluments Clause]]; and (4) whether Trump \"has accurately reported his finances to the Office of Government Ethics and other federal entities.\"<ref name=DCCirDecision/>\n\nOn May 10, 2019, Neal, the chairman of the [[House Ways and Means Committee]], issued a separate subpoena to both the Treasury Department and Internal Revenue Service to hand over six years of President Trump's personal and business tax returns and grant access by May 17.<ref name=WaysMeansSub/> Neal stated that the committee aimed to obtain the tax records to evaluate \"the extent to which the I.R.S. audits and enforces the federal tax laws against a president.\"<ref name=WaysMeansSub/>\n\n====Trump administration defies subpoenas==== \nThe Trump administration refused to comply with the subpoenas.<ref name=Defies>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/17/politics/steve-mnuchin-tax-returns-repsonse/index.html|title=Mnuchin defies House Democrats' subpoenas for Trump's tax returns|author=Lauren Fox|date=May 17, 2019|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name=MnunchinRefusal>{{cite news|last=Rappeport|first=Alan|title=Steven Mnuchin Refuses to Release Trump's Tax Returns to Congress|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/06/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-mnuchin.html|access-date=May 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> On May 6, 2019, after weeks of delay, Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]] sent a letter to House Ways and Means Committee chair Neal, asserting that the subpoena lacked \"a legitimate legislative purpose\" and that \"the department may not lawfully fulfill the committee's request,\" although the IRS released president [[Richard Nixon]]'s tax returns the same day Congress requested them in 1973.<ref name=MnunchinRefusal/> The Trump's administration's [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]], through a memo written by [[Office of Legal Counsel]] head [[Steven Engel]], issued an opinion supporting Mnuchin's refusal to release Trump's tax returns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/14/us/politics/trump-tax-returns-justice-department.html|title=Justice Dept. Backs Mnuchin's Refusal to Release Trump's Tax Returns|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 14, 2019|access-date=June 17, 2019|first=Alan|last=Rappeport|author-link=Alan Rappeport}}</ref> This triggered a legal battle between the administration and Congress.<ref>Andrew Taylor & Jonathan Lemire, [https://apnews.com/ce215295783e419d8896d50bc7907107 Refusal to hand over Trump\u2019s tax returns sets up legal fight], Associated Press (May 7, 2019).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/mnuchin-rejects-democrats-demand-to-hand-over-trumps-tax-returns-all-but-ensuring-legal-battle/2019/05/06/5483f8ac-7022-11e9-9eb4-0828f5389013_story.html|title=Mnuchin rejects Democrats' demand to hand over Trump's tax returns, all but ensuring legal battle|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/justice-dept-issues-memo-backing-mnuchins-refusal-to-provide-trumps-tax-returns-to-congress/2019/06/14/3c8b3376-8ee7-11e9-b08e-cfd89bd36d4e_story.html|title=Justice Dept. issues memo backing Mnuchin's refusal to give Trump's tax returns to Congress|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/07/25/irs-turned-over-nixons-tax-returns-same-day-that-congressional-panel-asked-them/|title=IRS turned over Nixon's tax returns the same day that a congressional panel asked for them|website=Washington Post}}</ref> Neal criticized the administration's position, saying that its objections \"lack merit\" and that \"judicial precedent commands that none of the concerns raised can legitimately be used to deny the committee\u2019s request.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Jeff|title=House Democrats give IRS hard deadline of April 23 to turn over Trump tax returns, say administration's concerns 'lack merit'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/04/13/house-democrats-give-irs-hard-deadline-april-turn-over-trump-tax-returns-say-administrations-concerns-lack-merit/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2019, [[Mick Mulvaney]], Trump's acting [[White House Chief of Staff|White House chief of staff]], said that Trump's tax returns will \"never\" be released.<ref name=Rupar>{{cite web|last1=Rupar|first1=Aaron|title=Mick Mulvaney rewrites history, claims Trump never promised to release his tax returns|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/4/8/18300213/mick-mulvaney-trump-tax-returns-fox-news-sunday|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Itkowitz|first1=Colby|title=Mulvaney says Democrats will 'never' see Trump's tax returns|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mulvaney-says-democrats-will-never-see-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/07/e939deca-593a-11e9-a00e-050dc7b82693_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref> Trump and Mulvaney have argued that voters have no interest in Trump's tax returns and that the issue was \"litigated\" when Trump was elected to the presidency.<ref name=Rupar/><ref name=FOXdeadline>{{cite web|last=Re|first=Gregg|title=Treasury won't meet House Dems' deadline to provide Trump tax returns, Mnuchin says|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/mnuchin-says-treasury-wont-meet-house-dems-deadline-to-provide-trump-tax-returns.amp|publisher=[[Fox News]]|access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' revealed that it had acquired information about Trump's tax returns showing over one billion dollars in business losses with a decade in the red.<ref name=\"Red\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/07/politics/donald-trump-tax-returns-steve-mnuchin-richard-neal/index.html|title=The secret of why Donald Trump won't release his taxes|first=Chris|last=Cillizza|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, a Trump adviser speaking on condition of anonymity told [[Fox News]] that Trump has repeatedly questioned his aides about the status of the congressional request, and also asked about the \"loyalty\" of top IRS officials.<ref name=FOXdeadline/> Trump appointee [[Michael J. Desmond]], who as Chief Counsel of the IRS and Assistant General Counsel in the [[United States Department of the Treasury|Department of the Treasury]] is responsible for giving legal advice to the IRS commissioner, previously served as a tax advisor to the Trump Organization and also worked alongside two other longtime tax advisors to the Trump Organization. According to the ''[[New York Times]]'', on February 5, 2019, Trump asked [[Senate Majority Leader]] Mitch McConnell to speed up Desmond's confirmation and indicating that confirming Desmond was a higher priority to him than confirming [[William Barr]] for Attorney General.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Haberman|first1=Maggie|last2=Fandos|first2=Nicholas|title=Trump Asked That Confirmation of I.R.S. Counsel Be a Priority|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/04/us/politics/trump-michael-desmond-irs.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nTrump and his [[White House Press Secretary]] [[Sarah Sanders]], said that Trump would not release his tax returns while they are under audit,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-maneuvers-to-block-release-of-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/04/047b19e0-56f4-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|title=White House maneuvers to block release of Trump's tax returns|website=Washington Post|access-date=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405054133/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-maneuvers-to-block-release-of-trumps-tax-returns/2019/04/04/047b19e0-56f4-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> although nothing precludes a person from releasing tax returns that are under audit,<ref name=\"auto1\"/> a fact reaffirmed by IRS Commissioner Rettig.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bruggeman|first=Lucien|title=Treasury to miss Democrats' deadline for Trump's tax returns, he doubles down: 'I won't do it'|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/democrats-deadline-trumps-tax-returns-looms-doubles/story?id=62298329|publisher=[[ABC News]]|access-date=April 28, 2019}}</ref> Sanders also opined that Congress is not \"smart enough\" to examine Trump's tax returns,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Danner|first1=Chas|title=Sarah Sanders: Democrats Aren't 'Smart Enough' to Understand Trump's Tax Returns|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/04/sarah-sanders-democrats-wont-understand-trumps-taxes.html|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> although ten members of Congress are accountants, including three [[Certified Public Accountant]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levenson|first=Eric|title=Sarah Sanders says Congress wouldn't understand Trump's taxes. But 10 members are accountants|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/14/politics/trump-taxes-accountants-congress/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, Trump made a partially false statement that \"There\u2019s no law whatsoever\" that requires him to provide Congress his tax returns. While there is no law requiring Trump to publicly release his tax returns, federal law of [[Internal Revenue Code|IRS Code]] section 6103(f) does require Trump's (or anyone else's) tax returns to be given to Congress if they request it.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farley|first1=Robert|title=Trump Wrong About Tax Law|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2019/04/trump-wrong-about-tax-law/|website=[[FactCheck.org]]|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/6103|title=26 U.S. Code \u00a7 6103 - Confidentiality and disclosure of returns and return information|website=LII / Legal Information Institute}}</ref>\n\n====Trump's efforts in court to block House subpoenas====\n=====House Ways and Means Committee's suit to enforce subpoena to IRS=====\nOn May 17, 2019, Treasury Secretary Mnuchin again refused to hand over the records.<ref name=Defies/> On July 2, 2019, the House Committee on Ways and Means sued Mnuchin and IRS Commissioner Rettig to enforce the subpoena and obtain six years of Trump's tax returns.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/> The suit is pending before U.S. District Judge [[Trevor McFadden]], a Trump appointee, in the [[U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]].<ref name=Thomsen>Jacqueline Thomsen, [https://www.law.com/nationallawjournal/2019/09/20/the-obvious-answer-ex-house-attorneys-back-democrats-lawsuit-for-trump-tax-returns/ 'The Obvious Answer': Ex-House Attorneys Back Democrats' Lawsuit for Trump Tax Returns], ''National Law Journal'' (September 20, 2019).</ref> In September 2019, a bipartisan group of six former general counsels to the House of Representatives filed an [[amicus brief]] in the case, urging the court to reject Trump's claims that the House lacks standing to bring the case.<ref name=Thomsen/>\n\n=====''Trump v. Mazars USA, LLP'': Trump's efforts to block House Oversight Committee subpoena to accounting firm=====\n{{main|Trump v. Mazars USA, LLP}}\nOn May 20, 2019, U.S. District Judge [[Amit Mehta]] of the [[U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]], refused a request by Trump's attorneys to quash the subpoena from the House Oversight Committee directed to Trump's accounting firm, Mazars USA LLP, ruling that the subpoena must be complied with.<ref name=trumptaxloss>{{cite news|author=Jan Wolfe|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-court-mazars-idUSKCN1SQ29H|title=Trump loses lawsuit challenging subpoena for financial records|date=May 21, 2019|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=DCtDDCOversight>''[https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20190523g19 Trump v. Committee on Oversight & Reform of U.S. House of Representatives]'', 380 F. Supp. 3d 76 (D.D.C. 2019).</ref> The district court held that the subpoena was well within Congress's broad investigative powers and rejected Trump's claim that the subpoena to Mazars was \"a usurpation of an exclusively executive or judicial function.\"<ref name=DCtDDCOversight/>\n\nTrump then appealed to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia]], which heard [[oral argument]] on July 12, 2019, and then issued a ruling against Trump on October 11, 2019. In its 2&ndash;1 ruling, the court of appeals upheld the lower court's ruling, holding that \"contrary to the President's arguments, the Committee possesses authority under both the House Rules and the Constitution to issue the subpoena\" for eight years of tax returns to Mazars, and that Mazars therefore \"must comply\" with the subpoena.<ref name=FahrentholdDCCir>David A. Fahrenthold, Spencer S. Hsu & Ann E. Marimow, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/legal-issues/appeals-court-rules-against-trump-in-fight-with-congress-over-presidents-accounting-firm-records/2019/10/11/42933894-b9ea-11e9-b3b4-2bb69e8c4e39_story.html Appeals court rules against Trump in fight with Congress over president\u2019s accounting firm records], ''Washington Post'' (October 11, 2019).</ref><ref name=Hemel>Daniel Hemel, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/10/14/how-trump-can-put-off-his-tax-return-case-until-after-election/ How Trump can put off his tax return case until after the election], ''Washington Post'' (October 14, 2019).</ref> The 66-page majority opinion was written by Judge [[David S. Tatel]], joined by [[Patricia A. Millett]]; Judge [[Neomi Rao]], a Trump appointee, dissented.<ref name=FahrentholdDCCir/> Trump's motion for rehearing ''[[en banc]]'' (i.e., before the entire D.C. Circuit) was denied on November 13, 2019, on an 8&ndash;3 vote.<ref name=Marimow>Ann E. Marimow, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/legal-issues/congress-can-seek-eight-years-of-trumps-tax-records-appeals-court-rules/2019/11/13/b4fc8002-fc07-11e9-8906-ab6b60de9124_story.html Congress can have access to eight years of Trump's tax records, appeals court orders], ''Washington Post'' (November 13, 2019).</ref><ref>''[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/6548874/Mazars-20191113.pdf Trump v. Mazars USA LLP]'' denial of rehearing ''en banc'', No. 19-5142 (D.C. Cir. Nov. 13, 2019).</ref> The ruling was the second appeals court decision within ten days against Trump regarding release of his tax returns.<ref name=Marimow/> \n\nTrump subsequently filed a petition for a [[writ of certiorari]] to the Supreme Court of the United States, asking the Court to review the case.  On December 13, 2019, the Supreme Court decided to review both the ''Trump v. Mazars US, LLP'' case (Supreme Court No. 19-715) and the ''Trump v. Deutsche Bank AG'' case (Supreme Court number 19-760). The court consolidated both cases and indicated that the cases would be set for [[oral argument]] sometime in the March 2020 argument session.<ref name=LiptakCertGranted>Adam Liptak, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/13/us/supreme-court-trump-financial-records.html Supreme Court to Rule on Release of Trump's Financial Records], ''New York Times'' (December 13, 2019).</ref><ref name=OrdersList>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/121319zr_1a7d.pdf Order List: December 13, 2019], Supreme Court of the United States.</ref> The Second Circuit's [[Appellate procedure in the United States|mandate]] was stayed pending the Supreme Court's decision in the case.<ref name=OrdersList/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/18/us/politics/trump-supreme-court-tax-returns.html|title=Chief Justice Gives Trump Temporary Reprieve in Financial Records Case|first=Adam|last=Liptak|date=November 18, 2019|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> The Court's decision in the case is believed to be a likely [[landmark ruling]] on how far presidents may resist subpoenas or other demands for information from the Congress and from prosecutors.<ref name=LiptakCertGranted/>\n\n===California primary election law===\nOn July 30, 2019, California governor [[Gavin Newsom]] signed the Presidential Tax Transparency and Accountability Act (S.B. 27), a law requiring candidates for president and California governor, as a condition for gaining California [[ballot access]], to release their most recent five years of federal tax returns at least 98 days ahead of the primary election (which would be November 26, 2019, for the 2020 primaries, since the California primary is on March 3, 2020).<ref name=BeckerSullivan>Stephanie Becker & Kate Sullivan, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/21/politics/california-tax-returns-trump/index.html California Supreme Court says law requiring presidential candidates to turn over tax returns is invalid], CNN (November 21, 2019).</ref><ref name=\"nytimes-30jul2019\">{{cite news|last1=Medina|first1=Jennifer|last2=Karni|first2=Annie|title=California Requires Trump Tax Returns Under New Election Law|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/30/us/politics/california-trump-tax-returns.html|access-date=July 30, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-30jul2019\">{{cite news|title=California governor signs law that would require Trump to release tax returns|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jul/30/california-governor-signs-law-that-would-require-trump-to-release-tax-returns|access-date=July 30, 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTrump immediately sued the State of California, seeking to block implementation of the law, asserting that the law is unconstitutional.<ref name=CalInjunction>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-09-19/trump-tax-returns-federal-court-challenge-california|title=Federal judge blocks California law to force disclosure of Trump's tax returns|date=September 19, 2019|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|author=John Myers}}</ref> On September 19, 2019, U.S. District Judge [[Morrison C. England]] issued a temporary injunction blocking the law from taking effect.<ref name=CalInjunction/> California appealed; [[California Secretary of State]] [[Alex Padilla]] said: \"Our elected leaders have a legal and moral obligation to be transparent with voters about potential conflicts of interest. This law is fundamental to preserving and protecting American democracy.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=John Myers|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-10-01/california-appeal-judge-trump-tax-returns|title=California will appeal judge's decision to block law requiring Trump's tax returns|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] dismissed California's appeal of the federal district court decision as [[Mootness|moot]], in light of the California Supreme Court's decision (see below).<ref>Daniel Tay, [https://www.law360.com/articles/1229287/9th-circ-tosses-suits-on-calif-s-invalidated-tax-return-law 9th Circ. Tosses Suits On Calif.'s Invalidated Tax Return Law], ''[[Law360]]'' (December 17, 2019).</ref>\n\nThe law was separately challenged in state court, and in November 2019, the [[California Supreme Court]] unanimously invalidated the law, meaning that Trump will not have to release his tax returns to get on the primary ballot in California in 2020.<ref name=BeckerSullivan/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article237248624.html|title=California can\u2019t force Donald Trump to release tax returns, state Supreme Court rules|last=Anderson|first=Bryan|date=November 21, 2019|website=The Sacramento Bee|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> Chief Justice [[Tani Gorre Cantil-Sakauye]] wrote that \"The Legislature may well be correct that a presidential candidate's income tax returns could provide California voters with important information\" but that the requirement to release the returns conflicted with the [[California Constitution]]'s \"specification of an inclusive open presidential primary ballot.\"<ref name=BeckerSullivan/>\n\n===New York TRUST Act===\nIn May 2019, the [[New York State Senate]] passed the TRUST Act which would amend state law to permit the commissioner of [[New York State Department of Taxation and Finance|the state Department of Taxation and Finance]] to release any state tax return requested by the leaders of the [[House Ways and Means Committee]], the [[Senate Finance Committee]] or the [[Joint Committee on Taxation]] for any \"specific and legitimate legislative purpose.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/ny-state-senate-passes-bill-allowing-congress-get-trump-tax-n1003396|title=N.Y. state Senate passes bill allowing Congress to get Trump tax returns; The state Senate also passed legislation that would make it easier for the state to prosecute individuals who were pardoned by the president.|author=Allan Smith|date=May 8, 2019|publisher=NBC News|access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/new-york-senate-passes-bill-to-let-congress-see-president-trumps-state-tax-returns|title=New York Senate Passes Bill to Let Congress See President Trump's State Tax Returns|author=Matt Naham|date=May 8, 2019|website=LawAndCrime.com|access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref> The [[New York State Assembly]] approved the bill on May 22, sending it to the governor.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/22/nyregion/trump-state-tax-returns.html|title=New York Passes Bill Giving Congress a Way to Get Trump's State Tax Returns|first=Jesse|last=McKinley|date=May 22, 2019|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> On July 8 [[List of governors of New York|Gov.]] [[Andrew M. Cuomo]] signed the bill.<ref name=\"McKinley2019\"/> \n\nTrump sued the State and the House Ways and Means Committee fifteen days later to block release of the tax returns.<ref name=\"TrumpSuitNY\"/> In November 2019, Trump's suit was dismissed on [[personal jurisdiction]] grounds.<ref name=\"Polantz\"/>\n\n===''Trump v. Vance'': Trump's challenge to Manhattan district attorney subpoena===\nIn late August 2019,<ref name=TurnOver/> soon after opening an investigation into [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal|hush-money payments to Stormy Daniels]], the [[New York County District Attorney|Manhattan district attorney's office]] issued a subpoena to Trump's accounting firm, [[Mazars|Mazars USA]], for eight years of Trump's individual tax returns and corporate tax records for the Trump Organization.<ref name=TurnOver/><ref name=EightYearsSubpoenaed>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/16/nyregion/trump-tax-returns-cy-vance.html|title=8 Years of Trump Tax Returns Are Subpoenaed by Manhattan D.A.|last1=Rashbaum|first1=William K.|last2=Protess|first2=Ben|date=September 16, 2019|work=New York Times|access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref> The existence of the subpoena was first reported by the ''New York Times'' in September 2019.<ref name=EightYearsSubpoenaed/>\n\nTrump sought to quash the subpoena in [[United States federal court|federal court]], contending that a sitting president enjoys \"absolute immunity from criminal process of any kind.\"<ref name=TurnOver/> In court filings in September 2019, New York prosecutors rejected Trump's claim that he has \"sweeping immunity\" from a criminal probe while he is in office, writing that Trump was \"seeking to invent and enforce a new presidential 'tax return privilege,' on the theory that disclosing information in a tax return will necessarily reveal information that will somehow impede the functioning of a President, sufficiently to meet the test of irreparable harm.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/23/new-york-trump-tax-returns-1763041|title=New York prosecutors reject Trump's immunity claim in tax returns case|author=Toby Ecker|date=September 23, 2019|website=politico.com|access-date=September 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/fadec6510fc543e497d594c0db8ecd10|title=Prosecutor says Trump wants 'sweeping immunity' in tax fight|author=Larry Neumeister|date=September 23, 2019|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nOn October 7, 2019, Judge [[Victor Marrero]] of the [[U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York]] rejected Trump's effort to prevent his tax returns from being turned over to the New York grand jury, and ordered Trump to comply with a subpoena. In a 75-page opinion, the court called Trump's contention an overreach of executive power that is \"repugnant to the nation's governmental structure and constitutional values.\"<ref name=TurnOver/><ref name=SDNYDecision/> Enforcement of the subpoena was temporarily delayed pending consideration by the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]].<ref name=TurnOver/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/07/politics/trump-tax-returns-lawsuit/index.html|title=Judge dismisses Trump request to keep taxes secret in New York|last=Orden|first=Erica|publisher=CNN|date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> Later the same month, [[oral argument]] before the Second Circuit took place before a three-judge panel of Chief Judge [[Robert A. Katzmann]], Judge [[Denny Chin]], and Judge [[Christopher F. Droney]]. Trump's private lawyer, William S. Consovoy, argued that a president enjoyed absolute \"presidential immunity\" from all investigation and criminal process while in office; responding to a hypothetical from the court, Consovoy said the president should be shielded even if he hypothetically committed murder on [[Fifth Avenue]] in Manhattan.<ref name=ImmunityClaim>Ann E. Marimow & Jonathan O'Connell, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/legal-issues/ny-based-appeals-court-to-decide-whether-manhattan-da-can-get-trumps-tax-returns/2019/10/22/8c491346-ef6e-11e9-8693-f487e46784aa_story.html Trump lawyer argues a sitting president would be immune from prosecution even if he were to shoot someone], ''Washington Post'' (October 22, 2019).</ref><ref>Lauren Aratani, [https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/23/donald-trump-immune-shoot-fifth-avenue-murder Trump couldn't be prosecuted if he shot someone on Fifth Avenue, lawyer claims], ''The Guardian'' (October 23, 2019).</ref><ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?465172-1/circuit-hears-oral-argument-president-trumps-tax-returns-audio-only&live Oral argument audiorecording and transcript], ''Trump v. Vance'', [[C-SPAN]], October 23, 2019</ref> In response, counsel for the Manhattan District Attorney's Office told the court that \"there is no such thing as presidential immunity for tax returns\" and noted that tax returns are frequently subpoenaed in financial investigations.<ref name=ImmunityClaim/>\n\nOn November 4, 2019, a three-judge panel of the Second Circuit unanimously ruled that Mazars must comply with the subpoena and hand over eight years of Trump's tax returns.<ref name=WeiserLiptak/><ref name=2dCir/> The court held that the president is not immune from \"the enforcement of a state grand jury subpoena directing a third party to produce non-privileged material, even when the subject matter under investigation pertains to the President\" and that a state grand jury may permissibly issue subpoenas \"in aid of its investigation of potential crimes committed by persons within its jurisdiction, even if that investigation may in some way implicate the President.\"<ref name=2dCir/> Noting that \"the President concedes that his immunity lasts only so long as he holds office and that he could therefore be prosecuted after leaving office,\" the Second Circuit ruled that there \"is no obvious reason why a state could not begin to investigate a President during his term and, with the information secured during that search, ultimately determine to prosecute him after he leaves office.\"<ref name=2dCir/> \n\nTrump subsequently filed a petition for a [[writ of certiorari]] to the Supreme Court, asserting that the grand-jury subpoena directed to him violates [[Article II of the United States Constitution|Article II]] and the [[Supremacy Clause]] of the Constitution. In December 2019, the Court agreed to hear the appeal, and initially set [[oral arguments]] for March 2020.<ref name=VanceDocket>[https://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/trump-v-vance/ Case Files: ''Trump v. Vance''] (S. Ct. No. 19-635), [[SCOTUSblog]].</ref> However, the Supreme Court indefinitely postponed oral argument in the case due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].<ref>Joan Biskupic, [https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/03/politics/supreme-court-trump-documents-coronavirus/index.html Delay in Trump's financial documents cases clouds House power on investigations], CNN (April 3, 2090).</ref>\n\n===Whistleblower complaint regarding interference in mandatory IRS audit process===\nOn July 29, 2019, a career IRS official filed a whistleblower complaint with the [[House Ways and Means Committee]], [[United States Senate Committee on Finance|Senate Finance Committee]], and [[Treasury Inspector General for Tax Administration]], stating that at least one [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department]] official had inappropriately interfered in the audit process for the tax returns of the president and vice president,<ref name=SteinHamburgerDawsey>{{cite news|author1=Jeff Stein|author2=Tom Hamburger|author3=Josh Dawsey|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/irs-whistleblower-said-to-report-treasury-political-appointee-might-have-tried-to-interfere-in-audit-of-trump-or-pence/2019/10/03/0c768b34-e52e-11e9-a331-2df12d56a80b_story.html|title=IRS whistleblower said to report Treasury political appointee might have tried to interfere in audit of Trump or Pence|work=The Washington Post|date=October 3, 2019}}</ref> which takes place annually in accordance with IRS policy.<ref>{{cite news|author=Naomi Jagoda|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/464469-tax-return-whistleblower-in-spotlight-amid-impeachment-fight|title=Tax-return whistleblower in spotlight amid impeachment fight|work=The Hill|date=October 6, 2019}}</ref> The possibility that political appointees interfered with audits conducted by career civil servants alarmed former IRS officials and legal experts.<ref name=SteinHamburgerDawsey/> Due to stringent laws regarding disclosure of tax information, the details of the complaint have not been made public.<ref name=SteinHamburgerDawsey/> However, Representative [[Richard E. Neal]], the Democratic chair of the House Ways and Means Committee, said in September 2019 that he was consulting legal counsel on whether the whistleblower's complaint could be publicly released.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jeff Stein|author2=Tom Hamburger|author3=Josh Dawsey|author4=Colin Wilhelm|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-27/democrat-weighs-releasing-complaint-about-irs-trump-tax-audit|title=Democrat Weighs Releasing Complaint About IRS Trump Tax Audit|work=Bloomberg|date=September 27, 2019}}.</ref>\n\nThe whistleblower's report was referred to by Neal and other House Democrats in the federal lawsuit regarding Trump's refusal to comply with a House Ways and Means Committee subpoena for the returns; in a filing, Neal wrote that the whistleblower's complaint presents credible evidence of \"potential 'inappropriate efforts to influence' the mandatory audit program\" and raises \"serious and urgent concerns,\" thereby bolsters the committee's case for obtaining the tax returns.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lorenzo|first1=Aaron|title=House Democrats say bolsters case for getting Trump's tax returns|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/20/tax-democrats-trump-1673427|access-date=October 1, 2019|work=[[Politico]]|date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019)]]\n*[[Wealth of Donald Trump]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Donald Trump}}\n{{Trump businesses}}\n[[Category:Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:United States tax law]]\n[[Category:Controversies of the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump controversies|Tax returns]]\n", "name_user": "2605:6001:e7c4:1e00:e85f:36b4:a5b4:97fb", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tax_returns_of_Donald_Trump"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Osma-Soria", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n|jurisdiction     = Diocese \n|name             = Osma-Soria \n|latin            = Dioecesis Oxomensis-Soriana\n|local            = Di\u00f3cesis de Osma-Soria\n|image            = Catedral del Burgo de Osma (Soria), Castilla, Espa\u00f1a.jpg\n|image_size       = 230px\n|caption          = [[Burgo de Osma Cathedral]]\n|country          = [[Spain]] \n|metropolitan     = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Burgos|Burgos]]\n|province         = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Burgos|Burgos]]\n|rite             = [[Latin liturgical rites|Latin Rite]]\n|established      = \n|cathedral        = [[Burgo de Osma Cathedral|Cathedral of the Assumption of Our Lady in Burgo de Osma]]\n|cocathedral      = [[Co-Cathedral of San Pedro, Soria|Co-Cathedral of St Peter in Soria]]\n|area_km2         = 10,328\n|population       = 95,700\n|population_as_of = 2013\n|catholics        = 76,900 \n|catholics_percent= 80.4\n|pope             = {{Incumbent pope}}\n|bishop           = [[Abilio Mart\u00ednez Varea]]\n|metro_archbishop = Francisco Gil Hell\u00edn\n|coadjutor        = \n|auxiliary_bishops= \n|map              = \n|website          = [http://www.osma-soria.org/ Website of the Diocese] \n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Osma-Soria ''' ({{lang-la|Oxomen(sis)\u2013Sorian(a)}}) is a [[Suffragan bishop|suffragan]] Latin [[diocese]] in the [[Ecclesiastical province]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Burgos|Burgos]], [[Province of Soria|Soria Province]], in the [[Castile and Le\u00f3n|Castilla y Leon]] region of northern [[Spain]].<ref name=CathHierOsma>{{cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|title=Diocese of Osma-Soria |website=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dosma.html|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]</ref><ref name=GCathOsma>{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Diocese of Osma-Soria (Italy)|publisher=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/osma0.htm |accessdate=June 16, 2018}} [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]</ref> Its [[cathedral]] episcopal see is Catedral de Santa Mar\u00eda de la Asunci\u00f3n, dedicated to the [[Assumption of Mary]], in [[Burgo de Osma-Ciudad de Osma|El Burgo de Osma]]. It also has a [[co-cathedral]], Concatedral de San Pedro, dedicated to [[Saint Peter|St. Peter]], in [[Soria]], and a [[minor basilica]]: Bas\u00edlica de Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de los Miagros Miagros, in [[\u00c1greda]], Soria, Castile and Le\u00f3n, Spain.\n\n== History ==\n* Established circa 600 as '''Diocese of Osma'''\n* Lost territory in 1077 to the [[Diocese of N\u00e1jera]]\n* Renamed on 9 March 1959 as Diocese of Osma-Soria, as [[Soria]] gets a co-cathedral\n\n== Statistics ==\n[[Image:burgo de osma nocturna.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Catedral de Santa Mar\u00eda de la Asunci\u00f3n and city walls]]\nAs per 2014, it pastorally served 80,000 Catholics (85.8% of 93,291 total) on 10,287&nbsp;km\u00b2 in 542 parishes and 19 missions with 128 priests (103 diocesan, 25 religious), 212 lay religious (38 brothers, 174 sisters) and 1 seminarian.\n\n==Episcopal ordinaries==\n(all [[Latin Rite]])\n:very incomplete : lacking first centuries\n\n;''Suffragan Bishops of Osma''\n* Pedro de Bourges, [[Benedictine Order]] (O.S.B.) (1101 \u2013 death 1109.08.02)\n* Raimundo (1109\u20131124), next Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Toledo|Toledo]] (Spain) (1124 \u2013 death 1152)\n* Beltr\u00e1n (1126 \u2013 death 1140.10.01)\n* Esteban (1141 \u2013 death 1147.09.01)\n* Juan (1148 \u2013 death 1174.04.28)\n* Bernardo (1174\u20131176)\n* Miguel, O.S.B. (1177\u20131184)\n* Garc\u00eda (1185\u20131186)\n* Mart\u00edn Baz\u00e1n (1188 \u2013 death 1201.07.27)\n* Diego de Acebes (1201 \u2013 1207.12.30)\n* [[Rodrigo Jim\u00e9nez de Rada]], [[Cistercian Order]] (O. Cist.) (1208 \u2013 1208 ? 27 Feb 1209) \n* Menendo (1210\u20131225)\n* Pedro Ram\u00edrez de Piedrola (1225\u20131230), next Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Pamplona|Pamplona]] (Spain) (1231 \u2013 death 1238.10.05)\n* Juan (1231 \u2013 1240.05.29), next Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Burgos|Burgos]] (Spain) (1240.05.29 \u2013 1246)\n* Pedro de Pe\u00f1afiel (1241 \u2013 death 1246.04.12)\n* Gil(les) (27 March 1247 \u2013 death 4 August 1261) \n* [[Agustin P\u00e9rez (bishop)|Agustin P\u00e9rez]] (18 Oct 1261 \u2013 death 12 April 1286) \n* [[Juan Alvarez (bishop)]] (4 May 1286 \u2013 death 20 Oct 1296) \n* Juan P\u00e9rez de Ascaron (1296 \u2013 death 1329)\n* Bernab\u00e9 (1329.10.20 \u2013 death 1351), previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Badajoz|Badajoz]] (Spain) (1324.07.27 \u2013 1329.10.20)\n* Gonzalo (1351\u20131354)\n* Alfonso Fernando de Toledo y Vargas, [[Augustinians]] (O.E.S.A.) (1354.10.25 \u2013 1363.10.13), later Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sevilla|Sevilla]] (Andalusia, southern Spain) (1363.10.13 \u2013 1366); previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Badajoz|Badajoz]] (Spain) (1353.02.13 \u2013 1354.10.25)\n* Lorenzo P\u00e9rez (1362.12.13 \u2013 death 1367)\n* [[Pedro Gomez Barroso]] (19 July 1368 \u2013 4 March 1373), next Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cuenca|Cuenca]] (Spain) (1373\u20131378)\n* [[Juan Garc\u00eda Palomeque]] (4 March 1373 \u2013 death 1374), previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Badajoz|Badajoz]] (Spain) (1354.10.25 \u2013 1373.03.04) \n* Juan de Villareal (1374 \u2013 death 1379.02.22)\n* [[Pedro Fern\u00e1ndez de Fr\u00edas]] (21 March 1379 \u2013 resigned? 1404), ''also/next [[Pseudocardinal]]-Priest of [[S. Prassede]] (1396? \u2013 1412.09.23\u25bc), [[Archpriest]] of [[Papal Basilica of St. Peter]] (1412 \u2013 1420.09.19\u25bc), promoted Pseudo[[cardinal-Bishop]] of [[Suburbicarian Diocese of Sabina]] (1412.09.23 \u2013 death 1420.09.19\u25bc) but also Pseudocardinal-Priest of above S. Prassede ''[[in commendam]]'' (1412.09.23 \u2013 1419.06.26?\u25bc) and next Pseudocardinal-Priest of S. Cecilia ''[[in commendam]]'' (1419.06.26 \u2013 1420.09.19\u25bc)\n*'' [[Apostolic Administrator]] [[Alfonso Carrillo de Albornoz]] (28 Nov 1408 \u2013 death 14 March 1434), while [[Pseudocardinal]]-Deacon of [[S. Eustachio]] (1408.09.22 \u2013 1418.08.01\u25bc); later (canonical) Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Sig\u00fcenza|Sig\u00fcenza]] (Spain) (1422 \u2013 ?), promoted [[Cardinal-Priest]] of [[Ss. Quattro Coronati]] (1423.01 \u2013 death 1434.03.14), Archpriest of [[Papal Archbasilica of St. John Lateran]] (1428 \u2013 1434.03.14)\n* Juan de Cerezuela y Luna (1422\u20131433), next Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sevilla|Sevilla]] (Spain) (1433 \u2013 1434), Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Toledo|Toledo]] (Spain) (1434 \u2013 1442)\n* [[Pedro de Castilla de Eril]] (22 April 1433 \u2013 6 April 1440), next Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Palencia|Palencia]] (Spain) (1440.04 \u2013 1461.04.28)\n* Roberto Moya (1440 \u2013 death 1453.11.13)\n* [[Pedro Garc\u00eda de Montoya]] (Huete) (9 Jan 1454 \u2013 death 18 Feb 1475)\n* Francisco de Santillana (1475.05.04 \u2013 1482.03.06), next Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of C\u00f3rdoba|C\u00f3rdoba]] (Spain) (1482.03.06 \u2013 1482 not possessed)\n**'' [[Apostolic Administrator]] Cardinal [[Pedro Gonz\u00e1lez de Mendoza]] (1482.07.08 \u2013 1482.11), while Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sevilla|Archdiocese of Sevilla]] (Spain) (1474.05.09 \u2013 1482.11.13), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Sig\u00fcenza|Diocese of Sig\u00fcenza]] (Spain) (1474.05.09 \u2013 1495.01.11), transferred Cardinal-Priest of [[S. Croce in Gerusalemme]] (1478.07.06 \u2013 death 1495.01.11); previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Calahorra y La Calzada|Calahorra y La Calzada]] (Spain) (1453.11.28 \u2013 1467.10.30), Bishop of above [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Sig\u00fcenza|Sig\u00fcenza]] (1467.10.30 \u2013 1474.05.09), created [[Cardinal-Priest]] of [[S. Maria in Domnica]] ''pro hac vice Title'' (1473.05.17 \u2013 1478.07.06); later [[Latin Patriarch of Alexandria]] (1482.11.13 \u2013 1495.01.11) and Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Toledo|Toledo]] (Spain) (1482.11.13 \u2013 1495.01.11)\n** ''[[Apostolic Administrator]] Cardinal [[Raffaele Riario]] (1483.01.15 \u2013 1493.05), while Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Pisa|Archdiocese of Pisa]] (Italy) (1479.09.17 \u2013 1499.06.03), transferred [[Cardinal-Deacon]] of [[S. Lorenzo in Damaso]] ''pro illa vice Deaconry'' (1480.05.05 \u2013 1503.11.29), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tr\u00e9guier|Diocese of Tr\u00e9guier]] (France) (1480.08.18 \u2013 1483.05.16), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Salamanca|Diocese of Salamanca]] (Spain) (1482.07.08 \u2013 1483), [[Chamberlain of the Holy Roman Church]] of [[Reverend Apostolic Camera]] (1483.01.24 \u2013 1521.07.09); previously [[Cardinal-Deacon]] of [[S. Giorgio in Velabro]] (1477.12.12 \u2013 1480.05.05), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Camerino|Diocese of Camerino]] (Italy) (1478.07.27 \u2013 1479.09.17), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cuenca|Diocese of Cuenca]] (Spain) (1479.08.13 \u2013 1482.07); later again Apostolic Administrator of Cuenca (1493.05.24 \u2013 1521.07.09), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuscanella|Diocese of Tuscanella]] (1498.08.28 \u2013 1506.09.16), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Viterbo|Diocese of Viterbo]] (Italy) (1498.08.28 \u2013 1506.09.16), [[Protodeacon]] of Sacred College of Cardinals (1503.09 \u2013 1503.11.29), promoted [[Cardinal-Bishop]] of [[Suburbicarian Diocese of Albano]] (1503.11.29 \u2013 1507.08.03), also Cardinal-Priest of [[S. Lorenzo in Damaso]] ''[[in commendam]]'' (1503.11.29 \u2013 1517.06.22), promoted Cardinal-Bishop of [[Suburbicarian Diocese of Sabina]] (1507.08.03 [1507.09.10] \u2013 1508.09.22), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Arezzo|Diocese of Arezzo]] (Italy) (1508.07.07 \u2013 1511.11.05), transferred Cardinal-Bishop of [[Suburbicarian Diocese of Porto e Santa Rufina]] (1508.09.22 \u2013 1511.01.20), [[Cardinal Vice-Dean]] of Sacred College of Cardinals (1508.09.22 \u2013 1511.01.20), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Savona|Diocese of Savona]] (Italy) (1508.12.05 \u2013 1516.04.09), transferred [[Cardinal-Bishop]] of [[Suburbicarian Diocese of Ostia\u2013Velletri]] (1511.01.20 \u2013 ?1517.06.22), [[Cardinal Dean]] of Sacred College of Cardinals (1511.01.20 \u2013 1521.07.09), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Malta|Diocese of Malta]] ([[Malta]]) (1516.05.23 \u2013 1520), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lucca|Diocese of Lucca]] (Italy) (1517.03.09 \u2013 1517.11.12), ?again Cardinal-Bishop of Ostia\u2013Velletri (?1517.07.24 \u2013 death 1521.07.09), Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Malaga|Diocese of Malaga]] (Balearic Spain) (1518.04.12 \u2013 1518.09.03), again Apostolic Administrator of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Pisa|Archdiocese of Pisa]] (Italy) (1518.09.03 \u2013 retired 1518.09.10) \n* [[Alfonso de Fonseca]] (1493 \u2013 death 1505), previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of \u00c1vila|\u00c1vila]] (Spain) (1469\u20131485), Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cuenca|Cuenca]] (Spain) (1485\u20131493)\n** [[Auxiliary Bishop]]: Garc\u00eda de Chinchilla, O.P. (1500.09.18 \u2013 death 1502), [[Titular Bishop]] of [[Byblus]] (1500.09.18 \u2013 1502)\n* [[Alfonso Enr\u00edquez]] (19 December 1505 \u2013 death 15 October 1523)\n** [[Auxiliary Bishop]]: Blas de Fernando, [[Cistercian Order]] (O. Cist.- (1507.04.19 \u2013 ?), Titular Bishop of above Byblus (1507.04.19 \u2013 ?)\n* [[Juan Pardo Tavera]] (31 December 1523 \u2013 8 June 1524), previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Ciudad Rodrigo|Ciudad Rodrigo]] (Spain) (1514.07.14 \u2013 1523.12.31); later Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santiago de Compostela|Santiago de Compostela]] (Spain) (1524.06.08 \u2013retired 1534.04.27), created [[Cardinal-Priest]] of [[S. Giovanni a Porta Latina]] (1531.04.27 \u2013 death 1545.08.01), Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Toledo|Toledo]] (Spain) (1534.04.27 \u2013 1545.08.01)\n* [[Garc\u00eda de Loaysa y Mendoza]], [[Order of Preachers]] (O.P.) (8 June 1524 \u2013 23 February 1532), previously Master of the [[Dominican Order]] (O.P.) (1518.05.23 \u2013 1524.06.08), created [[Cardinal-Priest]] of [[S. Susanna]] (1530.05.16 \u2013 death 1546.04.22), Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Sig\u00fcenza|Sig\u00fcenza]] (Spain) (1532.02.23 \u2013 1539.05.21), Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sevilla|Sevilla]] (Spain) (1539.05.21 \u2013 1546.04.22)\n* [[Pedro Gonz\u00e1lez Manso]] (13 March 1532 \u2013 death 12 February 1537), previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Guadix|Guadix]] (Spain) (1523.08.31 \u2013 1524.10.26), Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tui|Tui]] (Spain) (1524.10.26 \u2013 1525.07.03), Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Badajoz|Badajoz]] (Spain) (1525.07.03 \u2013 1532.03.13)\n* [[Pedro Alvarez de Acosta]] (21 May 1539 \u2013 death 20 February 1563), previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Porto|Porto]] (Portugal) (1507.02.12 \u2013 1535.01.08), Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Le\u00f3n in Spain|Le\u00f3n]] (Spain) (1535.01.08 \u2013 1539.05.21)\n* [[Honorato Juan]] (1 March 1564 \u2013 death 30 July 1566)\n* [[Francisco Tello Sandoval]] (3 March 1567 \u2013 13 June 1578), next Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Plasencia|Plasencia]] (Spain) (1578.06.13 \u2013 death 1580.07.08)\n* [[Alonso Vel\u00e1zquez]] (13 June 1578 \u2013 9 March 1583), next Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santiago de Compostela|Santiago de Compostela]] (Spain) (1583.03.09 \u2013 death 1587.01.14)\n* [[Sebasti\u00e1n P\u00e9rez (bishop)]] (9 May 1583 \u2013 death 27 July 1593 Died)\n* [[Mart\u00edn Garnica]] (27 April 1594 \u2013 death 20 November 1594 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaIV>{{cite book|url=http://sul-derivatives.stanford.edu/derivative?CSNID=00002719&mediaType=application/pdf|last1=Gauchat|first1=Patritius (Patrice)|title=HIERARCHIA CATHOLICA MEDII ET RECENTIORIS AEVI Vol IV|pages=268|date=1935|publisher=Libraria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|ISBN=}} ''(in Latin)''</ref>\n* [[Pedro Rojas Henr\u00edques]], [[Order of Saint Augustine]] (O.S.A.) (30 August 1595 \u2013 death 9 March 1602), previously Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Astorga|Astorga]] (Spain) (1591.03.06 \u2013 1595.08.30)\n* Enrique Enr\u00edquez, O.E.S.A. (1602.11.15 \u2013 1610.06.21), next Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Plasencia|Plasencia]] (Spain) (1610.06.21 \u2013 death 1622.01.22)\n* [[Fernando Acevedo Gonz\u00e1lez]] (July 1610 \u2013 2 June 1613), next Metropolitan Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Burgos|Burgos]] (Spain) (1613.06.02 \u2013 1629)\n* [[Francisco de Sosa]], O.F.M. (23 September 1613 \u2013 death 1618)<ref name=HierarchiaIV />\n* [[Crist\u00f3bal de Lobera y Torres]] (9 July 1618 \u2013 6 March 1623)<ref name=HierarchiaIV />\n* [[Alsono Mart\u00edn de Zu\u00f1iga]] (23 March 1623 \u2013 21 June 1630 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaIV />\n* [[Domingo Pimentel Z\u00fa\u00f1iga]], [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (2 October 1630 \u2013 18 July 1633)<ref name=HierarchiaIV />\n* [[Francisco Villafa\u00f1e]] (5 September 1633 \u2013 26 August 1639 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaIV />\n* [[Mart\u00edn Carrillo Alderete]] (9 June 1636 \u2013 1 July 1641)<ref name=HierarchiaIV /><ref name=CathHierMartCarrAld>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcaral.html \"Archbishop Mart\u00edn Carrillo Alderete\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved September 17, 2016 [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]</ref>\n* [[Antonio Vald\u00e9s Herrera]] (21 October 1641 \u2013 10 November 1653)<ref name=HierarchiaIV /><ref name=CathHierAntValHerr>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bvaldh.html \"Bishop Antonio Vald\u00e9s Herrera\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved September 17, 2016 [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]</ref>\n* [[Juan de Palafox y Mendoza]] (24 November 1653 \u2013 1 October 1659 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaIV />\n* [[Nicol\u00e1s Martinez (bishop)]], [[O.S.H.]] (21 June 1660 \u2013 1 Oct 1660 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaIV />\n* [[Alfonso Enr\u00edquez de Santo Tom\u00e1s]], [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (26 Sep 1661 \u2013 28 Jan 1664 Confirmed, [[Bishop of Plasencia]])<ref name=HierarchiaIV />\n* [[Pedro de Godoy]], [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (31 March 1664 \u2013 16 May 1672 Confirmed, [[Bishop of Sig\u00fcenza]])<ref name=HierarchiaIV /> \n* [[Antonio de Isla y Mena]] (8 August 1672 \u2013 17 Dec 1681 Died) \n* [[Sebasti\u00e1n de Ar\u00e9valo y Torres]], [[Order of Friars Minor]] (O.F.M.) (20 April 1682 \u2013 20 Jan 1704 Died)\n* [[Jorge C\u00e1rdenas Valenzuela]] (1704 \u2013 18 November 1705 Died)\n* [[Andr\u00e9s Soto de la Fuente]] (22 March 1706 \u2013 29 December 1714 Died)\n* [[Felipe Antonio Gil Taboada]] (5 July 1715 \u2013 4 March 1720)\n* [[Miguel Herrero Esgueva]] (15 April 1720 \u2013 20 January 1723)\n* [[Jacinto Valledor Fresno]] (12 April 1723 \u2013 12 February 1730 Died)\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Barnuevo]], O.S.B. (24 July 1730 \u2013 25 July 1735 Died)\n* [[Pedro de la Cuadra Achica]] (1 April 1736 \u2013 7 September 1741)\n* [[Juan Antonio Oru\u00f1a]]  (28 September 1744 \u2013 4 March 1748 Died)\n* [[Pedro Clemente de Ar\u00f3stegui]] (16 September 1747 \u2013 29 August 1760)\n* [[Jacinto Aguado y Chac\u00f3n]] (18 July 1762 \u2013 27 March 1764)\n* [[Bernardo Antonio Calder\u00f3n L\u00e1zaro]] (20 August 1764 \u2013 15 October 1786)\n* [[Joaqu\u00edn de Eleta]], O.F.M. (27 December 1786 \u2013 4 December 1788 Died)\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Constancio Andino]] (29 March 1790 \u2013 death Nov 1793)\n* [[Diego Melo Portugal]], [[Order of Saint Augustine]] (O.S.A.) (12 September 1794 \u2013 18 December 1795)\n* [[Antonio Tavira Almaz\u00e1n]] (27 June 1796 \u2013 14 August 1798)\n* [[Francisco Ignacio I\u00f1igo Angulo]] (25 September 1798 \u2013 8 January 1799)\n* [[Juan Moya (bishop)|Juan Moya]], O.F.M. (28 March 1799 \u2013 19 February 1801)\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Garnica]], [[Capuchin Franciscans]] (O.F.M. Cap.) (23 February 1801 \u2013 10 January 1810)\n* [[Juan Cavia Gonz\u00e1lez]] (19 August 1814 \u2013 23 December 1831)\n* [[Gregorio S\u00e1nchez y Jim\u00e9nez]] (Rubio), [[Hieronymites]] (O.S.H.) (17 December 1847 \u2013 27 September 1852)\n* [[Vicente Horcos y San Mart\u00edn]], [[Benedictine Order]] (O.S.B.) (27 September 1852 \u2013 13 January 1861)\n* [[Pedro Mar\u00eda Lag\u00fcera y Menezo]] (23 December 1861 \u2013 1892)\n* [[Victoriano Guisasola y Men\u00e9ndez]] (15 June 1893 \u2013 19 April 1897)\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Garc\u00eda Escudero y Ubago]] (19 April 1897 \u2013 22 March 1909)\n* [[Manuel Lago y Gonz\u00e1lez]] (25 August 1909 \u2013 4 May 1917)\n* [[Matteo M\u00fagica y Urrestarazu]] (22 February 1918 \u2013 26 October 1923)\n* [[Miguel de los Santos D\u00edaz y G\u00f3mara]] (18 December 1924 \u2013 28 January 1935)\n* [[Tom\u00e1s Guti\u00e9rrez Diez]] (1 April 1935 \u2013 11 November 1943)\n* [[Saturnino Rubio y Monti\u00e9l]] (9 December 1944 \u2013 1959 ''see below'')\n\n;''Suffragan Bishops of Osma-Soria=\n* [[Saturnino Rubio y Monti\u00e9l]]  (''see above'' 1959 \u2013 4 December 1969)\n* [[Teodoro Cardenal Fern\u00e1ndez]] (1 December 1969 \u2013 19 October 1983)\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Di\u00e9guez Reboredo]] (1 September 1984 \u2013 15 May 1987)\n* [[Braulio Rodr\